\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Rotation Matrices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Rotation matrices have always been a bane in my understanding of mechanical
 systems since the very beginning.
 I have heard terms like forward and backward transformations, passive and
 active rotations, Body-Centric vs Inertial representation without truly
 understanding them, and I have gotten confused with transforming the components
 of vectors verses the basis vectors of a frame.
 My aim at this document is to explore what rotation matrices really are
 by deriving them from a geometric perspective and only using coordinates
 when necessary.
 Along this journey I hope to clarify the terms like forward and backward
 transformations, passive and active rotations, and distinguish the difference
 between Body-Centric and Inertial representation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Throughout this document I will work in Euclidean spaces since we can measure
 distances and angles in this space, and where the inner product and cross
 product are well defined.
 These tools are necessary since they allow us to explore rotation matrices
 from a geometric perspective.
 Euclidean spaces also allow us to construct reference frames.
 Reference frames can be defined using the right-hand or left-hand convention.
 All of the frames used in this document will be right-handed frames; however,
 everything done in this note can be derived for left-handed frames.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to start this journey, we need to equip you with the proper tools
 to tackle such a dangerous adventure.
 These tools will consist of a quick introduction to vectors, reference
 frames, definitions of the inner product and cross product, and some notation.
 Once equipped with these tools, you will begin your journey by exploring
 the forward and backward transformations and active and passive transformations
 of vectors using arbitrary reference frames in 2-Dimensional Euclidean
 space.
 Make no mistake, the first part of this trek is steep and treacherous,
 but you will be rewarded with a short hike on gentle terrain as we repeat
 this exploration using standard reference frames in 2-Dimensional Euclidean
 space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
But don't you dare feel at ease, because the next stretch is the intense
 exploration of forward and backward transformations and active and passive
 transformations of vectors in 3-Dimensional Euclidean space! And only once
 you have made it this far, we can discuss the difference between Body-Centric
 and Inertial representation of rotations.
 Finally at the end of our journey together, we will sit down, take a deep
 breath, and quickly summarize the main points.
 And then you can walk away knowing that you are a better person, that you
 have journeyed where only a few dare to go.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Geometric Tools
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Vector"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To discuss rotation matrices from a geometric perspective, we need a basic
 understanding of vectors, reference frames, geometric concepts like the
 inner product and cross product, Euclidean space, several definitions,
 and some notation.
 Many of you will already have a solid understanding of this material and
 can comfortably skip to the next section; however, I still encourage you
 to read it because I might use different notation then what you are used
 to, and a refresher is always nice.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Vectors Frames
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A vector is an object in a space that is invariant to changes in coordinates
 or frames and is often used to express displacement, i.e., a direction and
 magnitude.
 I will denote all vectors with bold font, e.g., 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{i}$
\end_inset

, etc.
 Note that these are objects in a space, and they are not 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

tied down
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 by any coordinates.
 What makes vectors so amazing is that you can add them together (see figure
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:vector_addition"

\end_inset

) , and multiply them by scalars (see figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:vector_scalar"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/VectorProperty_Addition.pdf
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:vector_addition"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset space \hfill{}
\end_inset


\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/VectorProperty_Scale.pdf
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:vector_scalar"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These properties of vectors allows them to form a linear vector space.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Moon2000"

\end_inset

 A linear vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 over the field of scalars 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is a collection of vectors equipped with an additive operation 
\begin_inset Formula $+$
\end_inset

 and scalar multiplication operation 
\begin_inset Formula $\cdot$
\end_inset

 that satisfy the following properties: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 forms a group under addition, i.e., the following properties are satisfied
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
For any 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}+\mathbf{b}\in S$
\end_inset

.
 (The addition operation is closed)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For any 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, they commute under addition
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{a}+\mathbf{b}=\mathbf{b}+\mathbf{a}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
There is an identity element in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

, which we will denote as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{0}$
\end_inset

, such that for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\in S$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{a}+\mathbf{0}=\mathbf{0}+\mathbf{a}=\mathbf{a}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For every element 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}\in S$
\end_inset

 there is another element 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}\in S$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{a}+\mathbf{b}=\mathbf{0}.
\]

\end_inset

The element 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 is the additive inverse of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

 and is usually denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $-\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The addition operation is associative; for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(\mathbf{a}+\mathbf{b}\right)+\mathbf{c}=\mathbf{a}+\left(\mathbf{b}+\mathbf{c}\right).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
For any 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha,\beta\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{a},\mathbf{b}\in S$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\alpha\mathbf{b} & \in S\\
\alpha\left(\beta\mathbf{b}\right) & =\left(\alpha\beta\right)\mathbf{b}\\
\left(\alpha+\beta\right)\mathbf{b} & =\alpha\mathbf{b}+\beta\mathbf{b}\\
\alpha\left(\mathbf{a}+\mathbf{b}\right) & =\alpha\mathbf{a}+\alpha\mathbf{b}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
Some of you might be tempted to think of vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, but stop that! It is true that all vector spaces are isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, but I have said nothing about atlases and coordinates.
 Keep these vectors simply as objects that can be added together and scaled.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
I will denote linear vector spaces with the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 If it is necessary to specify the dimension of the vector space, I will
 use the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{n}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 denotes the dimension of the space.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Reference Frames
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Before we can talk about frames, let me introduce several definitions that
 might be familiar to you.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset S$
\end_inset

 be a finite subset of the vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 The elements of the subset are 
\series bold
linearly independent 
\series default
if 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{\left|U\right|}\alpha^{i}\mathbf{u}_{i}=0\iff\alpha^{i}=0;\,\mathbf{u}_{i}\in U,\,\alpha^{i}\in\mathbb{R},
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|U\right|$
\end_inset

is the cardinality of the subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout --Separator--

\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset S$
\end_inset

 
\series bold
spans
\series default
 the set 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 if every element of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 can be written as a linear combination of the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

 , i.e.,
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{s}=\sum_{i=1}^{\left|U\right|}\alpha^{i}\mathbf{u}_{i};\,\forall\mathbf{s}\in S,\,\mathbf{u}_{i}\in U.
\]

\end_inset

We denote that a subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset S$
\end_inset

 spans the space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 using the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $S=\text{span}\left(U\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout --Separator--

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The definition of a set spanning another set does not imply that the elements
 of the spanning set are linearly independent.
 If they are, then you have a basis of the original set.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A subset 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset S$
\end_inset

 that is linearly independent and spans 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 is a 
\series bold
basis
\series default
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 An element of the basis is called a 
\series bold
basis
\series default
 
\series bold
vector
\series default
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout --Separator--

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To solidify the definitions, let's go over a quick example.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{2}$
\end_inset

 form a basis in the vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\alpha^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2}=0\iff\alpha^{1}=\alpha^{2}=0,\,\alpha^{1},\alpha^{2}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 (
\emph on
linear independence
\emph default
) and 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}=\text{span}\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

, then the set 
\begin_inset Formula $U\coloneqq\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2}\right\} \subset S^{2}$
\end_inset

 is a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 An example of this basis is depicted in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:GenericBasis"

\end_inset

.
 By visual inspection you can see that the two basis vectors are linearly
 independent, and that any element in 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{2}$
\end_inset

 can be represented as a linear combination of the basis vectors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/GenericBasis.pdf
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:GenericBasis"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that we have an understanding of what a basis is, let's move onto reference
 frames.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A 
\series bold
reference frame
\series default
 is a basis equipped with an origin denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}=\left(O,U\right)$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $O$
\end_inset

 is point in the vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $U\subset S$
\end_inset

 is a basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout --Separator--

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A reference frame, or frame for short, allows us to measure a point relative
 to it's origin to create a distance vector.
 It also allows us to express vectors relative to it's basis using components.
 For example consider the scenario depicted in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:non-orthogonalBasis"

\end_inset

 which shows a frame 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{a}=\left(O,\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 a point 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=p-O$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/Nonstandard_Vector.pdf
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:non-orthogonalBasis"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The frame, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{a}$
\end_inset

, allows me to represent the distance vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 as a linear combination of the basis vectors using components such as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{v}^{a}=\alpha^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\alpha^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{i}\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 is the component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 with respect to (w.r.t.) to the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{i}$
\end_inset

, and the superscript 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is notation used to indicate that is being expressed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{a}$
\end_inset

.
 The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 can also be represented using matrix notation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{v}^{a}=\begin{bmatrix}\alpha^{1}\\
\alpha^{2}
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

where the first entry is the component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 w.r.t.
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and the second entry is the component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 w.r.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:non-orthogonalBasis"

\end_inset

, we can see that 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{1}=\alpha^{2}=1$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{v}^{a}=\mathbf{e}_{1}+\mathbf{e}_{2}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
I want to take a moment to stress that I have not associated coordinates
 to the vectors, i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{2}=2i+4j$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 are the orthogonal coordinates of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 I have left the basis vectors as objects somewhere in 2-dimensional Euclidean
 space, and I have represented the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 using the reference frame 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{a}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout --Separator--

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Quick aside: I will often omit the superscript on a vector when it isn't
 needed.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Inner Product
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Inner-Product"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inner product is a positive definite bilinear map, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \cdot,\cdot\right\rangle :H\times H\to\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, that takes two elements of a Hilbert space 
\begin_inset Formula $H$
\end_inset

 and maps them to an element in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inner product has four properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Commutative:
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \mathbf{v}_{1},\mathbf{v}_{2}\right\rangle =\overline{\left\langle \mathbf{v}_{2},\mathbf{v}_{1}\right\rangle }$
\end_inset

 where the overbar indicates complex conjugation.
 We will only work in the realm of real vectors, so this property is simplified
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \mathbf{v}_{1},\mathbf{v}_{2}\right\rangle =\left\langle \mathbf{v}_{2},\mathbf{v}_{1}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 .
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Distributive
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \mathbf{v}_{1}+\mathbf{v}_{2},\mathbf{v}_{3}\right\rangle =\left\langle \mathbf{v}_{1},\mathbf{v}_{3}\right\rangle +\left\langle \mathbf{v}_{2},\mathbf{v}_{3}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Scalar Multiplication
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle a\mathbf{v}_{1},\mathbf{v}_{2}\right\rangle =a\left\langle \mathbf{v}_{1},\mathbf{v}_{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle a\mathbf{v}_{1},b\mathbf{v}_{2}\right\rangle =ab\left\langle \mathbf{v}_{1},\mathbf{v}_{2}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Positive Definite
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \mathbf{v},\mathbf{v}\right\rangle >0$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $x\neq0$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \mathbf{v},\mathbf{v}\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset

 if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout --Separator--

\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can use the properties of the inner product to define the inner product
 of two vectors expressed in a reference frame.
 To show this let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{a}=\left(O_{a},\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 be an arbitrary reference frame in 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{2}$
\end_inset

 (2-dimensional Hilbert space), and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{1}=\beta^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\beta^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{2}=\gamma^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\gamma^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2}$
\end_inset

 be two vectors express in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{a}$
\end_inset

, then the inner product is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle \mathbf{v}_{1}^{a},\mathbf{v}_{2}^{a}\right\rangle =\sum_{k=1}^{2}\sum_{j=1}^{2}\left\langle \mathbf{e}_{k},\mathbf{e}_{j}\right\rangle \beta^{k}\gamma^{j}
\]

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2}\right\rangle =\left\langle \mathbf{e}_{2},\mathbf{e}_{1}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 are not necessarily 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inner product can be extended to any finite-dimension Hilbert space.
 For an 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 dimensional Hilbert space, 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{n}$
\end_inset

, the inner product is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\langle \mathbf{v}_{1}^{a},\mathbf{v}_{2}^{a}\right\rangle =\sum_{k=1}^{n}\sum_{j=1}^{n}\left\langle \mathbf{e}_{k},\mathbf{e}_{j}\right\rangle \beta^{k}\gamma^{j}\label{eq:innerProduct}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{1},\mathbf{v}_{2}\in H$
\end_inset

 and have components 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{i}$
\end_inset

 (respectively 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{i}$
\end_inset

) relative to the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
Two vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{1},\mathbf{v}_{2}\in H$
\end_inset

 are 
\series bold
orthogonal
\series default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \mathbf{v}_{1},\mathbf{v}_{2}\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset

 and are 
\series bold
orthonormal
\series default
 if 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle \mathbf{v}_{1},\mathbf{v}_{2}\right\rangle =0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \mathbf{v}_{1}\right\Vert =\left\Vert \mathbf{v}_{2}\right\Vert =1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout --Separator--

\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A 
\series bold
standard reference frame
\series default
, or standard frame, is a frame with an orthonormal basis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The inner product between two vectors can be simplified if they are being
 expressed in a standard reference frame.
 To demonstrate this, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{s}=\left(O,\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\ldots,\mathbf{e}_{n}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 be a standard reference frame in 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{n}$
\end_inset

 with an orthonormal basis, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{2}$
\end_inset

 be two vectors expressed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{s}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}_{1}^{s} & =\sum_{k=1}^{n}\beta^{k}\mathbf{e}_{k}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{v}_{2}^{s}=\sum_{j=1}^{n}\gamma^{k}\mathbf{e}_{j},
\]

\end_inset

then
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle \mathbf{v}_{1},\mathbf{v}_{2}\right\rangle =\sum_{k=1}^{n}\sum_{j=1}^{n}\left\langle \mathbf{e}_{k},\mathbf{e}_{j}\right\rangle \beta^{k}\gamma^{j}
\]

\end_inset

which can be simplified using the orthonormal property 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left\langle \mathbf{e}_{k},\mathbf{e}_{j}\right\rangle =\begin{cases}
1 & \text{if }k=j\\
0 & \text{else}
\end{cases},\,k,j\in\left\{ 1,\ldots,n\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left\langle \mathbf{v}_{1}^{s},\mathbf{v}_{2}^{s}\right\rangle  & =\sum_{k=1}^{n}\left\langle \mathbf{e}_{k},\mathbf{e}_{j}\right\rangle \beta^{k}\gamma^{k}\nonumber \\
 & =\sum_{k=1}^{n}\beta^{k}\gamma^{k}.\label{eq:simplifiedInnerProduct}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We often use the standard inner product, denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $H\times H\mapsto H\cdot H$
\end_inset

, since it is used to measure the magnitude of a vector and because it has
 the angle identity 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{v}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{v}_{2}=\left\Vert \mathbf{v}_{1}\right\Vert \left\Vert \mathbf{v}_{2}\right\Vert \cos\theta
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \mathbf{v}_{i}\right\Vert =\sqrt{\left\langle \mathbf{v}_{i},\mathbf{v}_{i}\right\rangle };\,\mathbf{v}_{i}\in H,\,i\in\left\{ 1,2\right\} $
\end_inset

 is the Euclidean norm, or magnitude, of the vector, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the angle between the vectors, and 
\begin_inset Formula $H\cdot H$
\end_inset

 denotes the standard inner product.
 From the angle identity of the standard inner product, we can see that
 the standard inner product is a measure of how much one vector is in the
 direction of another.
 If the vectors are unit length, the relation between the standard inner
 product of two vectors and the angle between the vectors is also simplified
 to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{v}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{v}_{2}=\cos\theta.\label{eq:simplified_inner_angle}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Cross Product
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The cross product is defined only in three dimensional vector space 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{3}$
\end_inset

 and is denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\cdot\times\cdot\right):S^{3}\times S^{3}\to S^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 The cross product maps two vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 to another vector in 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 that is orthogonal to both the first two vectors with a direction given
 by the right-hand rule and a magnitude equal to the area of the parallelogram
 that the vectors span.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Some common properties of the cross product are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
The self cross product of a vector is the zero vector
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\times\mathbf{v}=0$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Anticommutative
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{1}\times\mathbf{v}_{2}=-\left(\mathbf{v}_{2}\times\mathbf{v}_{1}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Distributive
\emph default
 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{1}\times\left(\mathbf{v}_{2}+\mathbf{v}_{3}\right)=\mathbf{v}_{1}\times\mathbf{v}_{2}+\mathbf{v}_{1}\times\mathbf{v}_{3}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate

\emph on
Scalar Multiplication
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a\mathbf{v}_{1}\right)\times\mathbf{v}_{2}=\mathbf{v}_{1}\times\left(a\mathbf{v}_{2}\right)=a\left(\mathbf{v}_{1}\times\mathbf{v}_{2}\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
If vectors are being expressed in a frame, their cross product is calculated
 as follows.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{a}=\left(O_{a},\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2},\mathbf{e}_{3}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 be an arbitrary frame in 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{3}$
\end_inset

 whose basis is not necessarily orthogonal or unit length, and let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}_{1}^{a} & =\alpha^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\alpha^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2}+\alpha^{3}\mathbf{e}_{3}\\
\mathbf{v}_{2}^{a} & =\beta^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\beta^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2}+\beta^{3}\mathbf{e}_{3}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

be two vectors expressed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{a}$
\end_inset

.
 the cross product of these two vectors is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}_{1}\times\mathbf{v}_{2} & =\left(\alpha^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\alpha^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2}+\alpha^{3}\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\times\left(\beta^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\beta^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2}+\beta^{3}\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\\
 & =\alpha^{1}\beta^{1}\left(\mathbf{e}_{1}\times\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)+\alpha^{1}\beta^{2}\left(\mathbf{e}_{1}\times\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)+\alpha^{1}\beta^{3}\left(\mathbf{e}_{1}\times\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\\
 & +\alpha^{2}\beta^{1}\left(\mathbf{e}_{2}\times\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)+\alpha^{2}\beta^{2}\left(\mathbf{e}_{2}\times\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)+\alpha^{2}\beta^{3}\left(\mathbf{e}_{2}\times\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\\
 & +\alpha^{3}\beta^{1}\left(\mathbf{e}_{3}\times\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)+\alpha^{3}\beta^{2}\left(\mathbf{e}_{3}\times\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)+\alpha^{3}\beta^{3}\left(\mathbf{e}_{3}\times\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which can be simplified to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}_{1}\times\mathbf{v}_{2} & =\left(\alpha^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\alpha^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2}+\alpha^{3}\mathbf{k}\right)\times\left(\beta^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\beta^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2}+\beta^{3}\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\\
 & =\alpha^{1}\beta^{1}\left(0\right)+\alpha^{1}\beta^{2}\left(\mathbf{e}_{1}\times\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)+\alpha^{1}\beta^{3}\left(\mathbf{e}_{1}\times\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\\
 & +\alpha^{2}\beta^{1}\left(\mathbf{e}_{2}\times\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)+\alpha^{2}\beta^{2}\left(0\right)+\alpha^{2}\beta^{3}\left(\mathbf{e}_{2}\times\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\\
 & +\alpha^{3}\beta^{1}\left(\mathbf{e}_{3}\times\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)+\alpha^{3}\beta^{2}\left(\mathbf{e}_{3}\times\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)+\alpha^{3}\beta^{3}\left(0\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This expression cannot be simplified further without knowing the cross product
 of the basis vectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{a}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A standard reference frame, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{s}=\left(O_{s},\left\{ \mathbf{i},\mathbf{j},\mathbf{k}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

, in 
\begin_inset Formula $S^{3}$
\end_inset

 has the cross product identities
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{i}\times\mathbf{j} & =\mathbf{k}\\
\mathbf{j}\times\mathbf{k} & =\mathbf{i}\\
\mathbf{k}\times\mathbf{i} & =\mathbf{j}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which implies by the anitcommutative property
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{j}\times\mathbf{i} & =-\mathbf{k}\\
\mathbf{k}\times\mathbf{j} & =-\mathbf{i}\\
\mathbf{i}\times\mathbf{k} & =-\mathbf{j}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{i}\times\mathbf{i}=\mathbf{j}\times\mathbf{j}=\mathbf{k}\times\mathbf{k}=0.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These identities allow us to simplify the cross product of two vectors expressed
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{s}$
\end_inset

.
 To demonstrate this, let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}_{1} & =\alpha^{1}\mathbf{i}+\alpha^{2}\mathbf{j}+\alpha^{3}\mathbf{k}\\
\mathbf{v}_{2} & =\beta^{1}\mathbf{i}+\beta^{2}\mathbf{j}+\beta^{3}\mathbf{k}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

be two vectors expressed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{s}$
\end_inset

 then their cross product is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}_{1}^{s}\times\mathbf{v}_{2}^{s} & =\left(\alpha^{1}\mathbf{i}+\alpha^{2}\mathbf{j}+\alpha^{3}\mathbf{k}\right)\times\left(\beta^{1}\mathbf{i}+\beta^{2}\mathbf{j}+\beta^{3}\mathbf{k}\right),\\
 & =\alpha^{1}\beta^{1}\left(\mathbf{i}\times\mathbf{i}\right)+\alpha^{1}\beta^{2}\left(\mathbf{i}\times\mathbf{j}\right)+\alpha^{1}\beta^{3}\left(\mathbf{i}\times\mathbf{k}\right)\\
 & +\alpha^{2}\beta^{1}\left(\mathbf{j}\times\mathbf{i}\right)+\alpha^{2}\beta^{2}\left(\mathbf{j}\times\mathbf{j}\right)+\alpha^{2}\beta^{3}\left(\mathbf{j}\times\mathbf{k}\right)\\
 & +\alpha^{3}\beta^{1}\left(\mathbf{k}\times\mathbf{i}\right)+\alpha^{3}\beta^{2}\left(\mathbf{k}\times\mathbf{j}\right)+\alpha^{3}\beta^{3}\left(\mathbf{k}\times\mathbf{k}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Evaluating the cross products yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}_{1}\times\mathbf{v}_{2} & =\alpha^{1}\beta^{1}\left(0\right)+\alpha^{1}\beta^{2}\left(\mathbf{k}\right)+\alpha^{1}\beta^{3}\left(-\mathbf{j}\right)\\
 & +\alpha^{2}\beta^{1}\left(-\mathbf{k}\right)+\alpha^{2}\beta^{2}\left(0\right)+\alpha^{2}\beta^{3}\left(\mathbf{i}\right)\\
 & +\alpha^{3}\beta^{1}\left(\mathbf{j}\right)+\alpha^{3}\beta^{2}\left(-\mathbf{i}\right)+\alpha^{3}\beta^{3}\left(0\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and collecting components gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{v}_{1}\times\mathbf{v}_{2}=\left(\alpha^{2}\beta^{3}-\alpha^{3}\beta^{2}\right)\mathbf{i}+\left(\alpha^{3}\beta^{1}-\alpha^{1}\beta^{3}\right)\mathbf{j}+\left(\alpha^{1}\beta^{2}-\alpha^{2}\beta^{1}\right)\mathbf{k}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Like the standard inner product, the cross product can be related to an
 angle.
 The formula for this relation is given as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{v}_{1}\times\mathbf{v}_{2}=\left\Vert \mathbf{v}_{1}\right\Vert \left\Vert \mathbf{v}_{2}\right\Vert \sin\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{n};\,\mathbf{v}_{i}\in S^{3}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \mathbf{v}_{i}\right\Vert ,\,i\in\left\{ 1,2\right\} $
\end_inset

 is the magnitude of the vector, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the angle between the vectors, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is a unit vector orthogonal to both 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{2}$
\end_inset

 whose direction is obtained using the right-hand rule.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Euclidean Space
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the rest of this journey together, we will be working in Euclidean Space.
 Euclidean space is an affine vector space equipped with the inner product
 and Euclidean norm.
 An affine vector space is a vector space whose origin can be translated
 to any point in space, i.e., vectors can translate in this space.
 An example of this is shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:VectorSpaceAffine"

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}=\left(O_{1},\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}=\left(O_{2},\left\{ \mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1},\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 are two frames in a two dimensional affine vector space where the origin
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 is denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{1}$
\end_inset

 and the origin of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In a regular vector space, all vectors must originate from the same point;
 however, in affine vector space the origin of vectors can be translated
 from one point to any point in space.
 In figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:VectorSpaceAffine"

\end_inset

, the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 shows the translations of the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\tilde{e}_{1}}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Euclidean space is also the space where geometry is done.
 Just like any vector space, any Euclidean space is isomorphic to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

.
 I will denote Euclidean spaces as 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

, and if it is necessary to specify the dimension of the space, I will denote
 it as 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{n}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 denotes the dimension.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/VectorSpace_Affine.pdf
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:VectorSpaceAffine"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Transformations in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{2}$
\end_inset

 with Arbitrary Reference Frames
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The beginning of this journey is difficult but rewarding.
 In this section, we will look at the forward and backward transformation
 between arbitrary reference frames, and passive and active transformations
 of vectors expressed in arbitrary frames.
 What I mean by arbitrary, is that they do not have to be standard reference
 frame.
 In fact, in this section most of the frames will not be standard reference
 frames.
 I'm doing this because people get too comfortable working with standard
 frames that they forget the true essence of what is happening.
 And I am not your guide that will protect you from the dangers of this
 journey.
 I want you to get bruised and scraped; your mind to melt and fizz.
 And if a brain cell bursts, all the better!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Forward Transformation 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Generic_Forward-Transformation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is often convenient to express a vector in one reference frame and then
 express it in a different reference frame.
 In order to do this we need to construct the 
\series bold
forward
\series default
 and 
\series bold
backward 
\series default
transformation between two reference frame.
 These transformations express the basis vectors in one frame w.r.t.
 the basis vectors in another frame.
 For example, consider the two frames arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}=\left(O_{1},\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}=\left(O_{2},\left\{ \mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1},\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 with coincident origins in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{2}$
\end_inset

 as depicted in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:basisTransformNonStandard"

\end_inset

.
 The forward transformation can either express the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

, or it can express the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The backward transformation is just the inverse of the forward transformations,
 i.e., if we define the forward transformation as the transformation that
 expresses the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

, then the backward transformation expresses the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In this document, we will always define the forward transformation as the
 transformation that expresses the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/TransformBasisNonStandard.pdf
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:basisTransformNonStandard"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's construct the forward transformation between the frames 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 as depicted in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:basisTransformNonStandard"

\end_inset

.
 We do this by expressing each basis vector of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 w.r.t.
 the basis vectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 That means we need to find components for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1} & =\alpha^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\alpha^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2},\\
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2} & =\beta^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\beta^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The components can be found by inspection of figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:basisTransformNonStandard"

\end_inset

 to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1} & =\frac{2}{3}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\frac{1}{3}\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2},\\
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2} & -\frac{1}{3}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\frac{1}{3}\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2};
\end{align*}

\end_inset

however, I want to show you how the standard inner product can be used to
 find the components since this will be useful later on.
 Taking the inner product of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}$
\end_inset

 with each basis vector of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 we get the system of equations 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1} & =\alpha^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}+\alpha^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\\
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2} & =\alpha^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}+\alpha^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which can be represented in matrix notation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\\
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}
\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1} & \mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\\
\mathbf{e}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1} & \mathbf{e}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\alpha^{1}\\
\alpha^{2}
\end{bmatrix},\label{eq:e1tilde_components}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where the components 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{2}$
\end_inset

 are the unknowns and the inner products can be measured.
 To simplify this problem, I will introduce a standard reference frame 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{3}=\left(O_{3},\left\{ \mathbf{i},\mathbf{j}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 as depicted in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:transformBasisNonStandardCoordinates"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/TransformBasisNonStandardCoordinates.pdf
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:transformBasisNonStandardCoordinates"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using this new reference frame I can express each basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{3}$
\end_inset

 as such
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{e}_{1} & =4\mathbf{i}+0\mathbf{j}\\
\mathbf{e}_{2} & =1\mathbf{i}+3\mathbf{j}\\
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1} & =3\mathbf{i}+1\mathbf{j}\\
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2} & =-1\mathbf{i}+1\mathbf{j},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and easily take their inner products.
 The first inner product is given in detail as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1} & =4*4\left(\mathbf{i}\cdot\mathbf{i}\right)+4*0\left(\mathbf{i}\cdot\mathbf{j}\right)+0*4\left(\mathbf{j}\cdot\mathbf{i}\right)+0*0\left(\mathbf{j}\cdot\mathbf{j}\right)\\
 & =4*4\left(1\right)+4*0\left(0\right)+0*4\left(0\right)+0*0\left(1\right)\\
 & =16
\end{align*}

\end_inset

I will not write out the other inner products in detail, but all of them
 are given below.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float table
placement h
wide false
sideways false
status open

