\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
<cell alignment="center" valignment="top" topline="true" bottomline="true" leftline="true" rightline="true" usebox="none">
\begin_inset Text

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}=2$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset
</cell>
</row>
</lyxtabular>

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "tab:innerProducts"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset

 Note that we omitted many of the inner products due to the symmetric property,
 i.e., 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{v}_{2}=\mathbf{v}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{v}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting the inner products of table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:innerProducts"

\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:e1tilde_components"

\end_inset

 yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{bmatrix}12\\
6
\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}16 & 4\\
4 & 10
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\alpha^{1}\\
\alpha^{2}
\end{bmatrix},
\]

\end_inset

and solving for the components gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{1}=\frac{2}{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{2}=\frac{1}{3}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The same process is done to express the basis 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 We begin with the desired component representation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}=\beta^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\beta^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2}.
\]

\end_inset

Taking the inner product of 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}$
\end_inset

 with each basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 we get the system of equations 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1} & =\beta^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}+\beta^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\\
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2} & =\beta^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}+\beta^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which can be represented in matrix notation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\\
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}
\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1} & \mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\\
\mathbf{e}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1} & \mathbf{e}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\beta^{1}\\
\beta^{2}
\end{bmatrix}.
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Substituting in the numerical values for the inner products yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{bmatrix}-4\\
2
\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}16 & 4\\
4 & 10
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\beta^{1}\\
\beta^{2}
\end{bmatrix},
\]

\end_inset

and solving for the components gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{1}=-\frac{1}{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{2}=\frac{1}{3}$
\end_inset

 which we did by inspection above.
 Now that we have the components, we can construct the forward transformation
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1} & =\frac{2}{3}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\frac{1}{3}\mathbf{e}_{2},\\
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2} & =-\frac{1}{3}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\frac{1}{3}\mathbf{e}_{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can represent represent the forward transformation using matrix notation
 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
F_{2}^{1} & =\begin{bmatrix}\alpha^{1} & \beta^{1}\\
\alpha^{2} & \beta^{2}
\end{bmatrix}\\
 & =\begin{bmatrix}\frac{2}{3} & -\frac{1}{3}\\
\frac{1}{3} & \frac{1}{3}
\end{bmatrix}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The subscript and superscript indicates that the forward transformation
 expresses the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Backward Transformation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:generic_Backward-Transformation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The backward transformation is the inverse of the forward transformation.
 Using the same process, we can express the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{e}_{1} & =\gamma^{1}\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+\gamma^{2}\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\\
\mathbf{e}_{2} & =\chi^{1}\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+\chi^{2}\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{i},\,i\in\left\{ 1,2\right\} $
\end_inset

 are the components.
 Taking the inner product of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 with the basis vectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 generates the system of equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1} & =\gamma^{1}\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+\gamma^{2}\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\\
\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2} & =\gamma^{1}\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}+\gamma^{2}\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which can be represented in matrix notation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\\
\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}
\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1} & \mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\\
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2} & \mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\gamma^{1}\\
\gamma^{2}
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

Substituting in the numerical values for each inner product from table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:innerProducts"

\end_inset

 yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{bmatrix}12\\
-4
\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}10 & -2\\
-2 & 2
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\gamma^{1}\\
\gamma^{2}
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

,
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and solving for the components gives 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{1}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{2}=-1$
\end_inset

.
 Using the same process to solve for 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}$
\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{1}=-1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi^{2}=2$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now that we have the components of the backward transformation, we can write
 it as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{e}_{1} & =1\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}-1\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\\
\mathbf{e}_{2} & =1\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+2\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which can be represented in matrix notation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
B_{1}^{2} & =\begin{bmatrix}\gamma^{1} & \chi^{1}\\
\gamma^{2} & \chi^{2}
\end{bmatrix}\\
 & =\begin{bmatrix}1 & 1\\
-1 & 2
\end{bmatrix}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can verify the forward and backward transformations using the fact that
 they are inverses of each other.
 This indicates that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{2}^{1}B_{1}^{2}=I.
\]

\end_inset

What this means is that if we use the forward transformation to transform
 the basis vectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 into the basis vectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

, and then use the backward transformation to transform the basis vectors
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 to the basis vectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

, we will end up with the same basis vectors.
 Let's now verify that the forward and backward transformations that we
 calculated are indeed inverses
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
F_{2}^{1}B_{1}^{2} & =I\\
\begin{bmatrix}\frac{2}{3} & -\frac{1}{3}\\
\frac{1}{3} & \frac{1}{3}
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}1 & 1\\
-1 & 2
\end{bmatrix} & =I\\
I & =I.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Passive Transformation of a Vector 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Nonstandard_Passive-Transformation-of"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A passive transformation of a vector changes which frame you are representing
 the vector in.
 This procedure is also commonly known as a change of basis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/VectorStransformNonStandard.pdf
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:vectorTransformNonStandard"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider two arbitrary frames 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 with coincident origins and a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{2}$
\end_inset

 as depicted in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:vectorTransformNonStandard"

\end_inset

.
 We have already calculated the forward and backward transformations in
 subsections 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Generic_Forward-Transformation"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:generic_Backward-Transformation"

\end_inset

, so I will not repeat those steps here, but they will be given again.
 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:forwardNonOthogonal"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{2}^{1}\coloneqq\begin{cases}
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1} & =\frac{2}{3}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\frac{1}{3}\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\\
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2} & =-\frac{1}{3}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\frac{1}{3}\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}
\end{cases},\text{ or }\begin{bmatrix}\frac{2}{3} & -\frac{1}{3}\\
\frac{1}{3} & \frac{1}{3}
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:backwardNonOrthogonal"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
B_{1}^{2}\coloneqq\begin{cases}
\mathbf{e}_{1} & =1\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}-1\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\\
\mathbf{e}_{2} & =1\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+2\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}
\end{cases},\text{ or }\begin{bmatrix}1 & 1\\
-1 & 2
\end{bmatrix}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 can be represented in both coordinate frames as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}^{1} & =1\mathbf{e}_{1}+1\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\\
\mathbf{v}^{2} & =2\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+1\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the superscript denotes which frame it is being expressed in.
 You can use the same process outlined in the previous subsections 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Generic_Forward-Transformation"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:generic_Backward-Transformation"

\end_inset

 to compute the components using the inner product, but we will skip that
 process and grab the components using visual inspection.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To transform the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{1}$
\end_inset

 to the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{2}$
\end_inset

, we start with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and use the backward transform defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:backwardNonOrthogonal"

\end_inset

 to transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{1}$
\end_inset

to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{2}$
\end_inset

 as follows
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v} & =1\mathbf{e}_{1}+1\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\\
 & =1\left(1\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}-1\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)+1\left(1\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+2\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)\\
 & =\left(1+1\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+\left(-1+2\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\\
 & =2\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+1\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\\
 & =\mathbf{v}^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which can be done using matrix notation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}^{2} & =\begin{bmatrix}1 & 1\\
-1 & 2
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}1\\
1
\end{bmatrix}\\
 & =B_{1}^{2}\mathbf{v}^{1}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Note that in order to transform the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{2}$
\end_inset

 we used the backward transformation.
 This implies that we can reverse the transformation using the forward transform
ation.
 To show this we begin the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and transform its components to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{1}$
\end_inset

 using the forward transformation defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:forwardNonOthogonal"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v} & =2\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+1\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\\
 & =2\left(\frac{2}{3}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\frac{1}{3}\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)+1\left(-\frac{1}{3}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\frac{1}{3}\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\\
 & =\left(2*\frac{2}{3}-\frac{1}{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(2*\frac{1}{3}+\frac{1}{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}\\
 & =1\mathbf{e}_{1}+1\mathbf{e}_{2}\\
 & =\mathbf{v}^{1}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which can be done using matrix notation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}^{1} & =\begin{bmatrix}\frac{2}{3} & -\frac{1}{3}\\
\frac{1}{3} & \frac{1}{3}
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}2\\
1
\end{bmatrix}\\
 & =F_{2}^{1}\mathbf{v}^{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The notation used to express this transform can be described as the transformati
on 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{2}^{1}$
\end_inset

 that transforms the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 This notation is easy to remember because same superscripts and subscripts
 are crossed out, and the remaining superscript indicates which frame it
 is.
 For example
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}^{1} & =F_{2}^{1}\mathbf{v}^{2}\\
 & =F_{\cancel{2}}^{1}\mathbf{v}^{\cancel{2}}\\
 & =\mathbf{v}^{1}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
We used the forward transformation to express the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and we used the backward transformation to transform the components of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{1}$
\end_inset

 to the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This shows that the components of a vector transform contravariently, or
 inversely, to the a change in basis; hence vectors are contravariant.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To build intuition of why vectors are contravariant, consider the simple
 example of measuring a person's height as depicted in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:person"

\end_inset

.
 In this figure we have two frames 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}=\left(O_{1},\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}=\left(O_{2},\left\{ \mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 with coincident origin.
 Note that in the figure the frame’s origins seems to be separated, but
 I did this for visual neatness.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/PersonMeasure.pdf
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:person"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can easily create the forward and backward transformations between the
 two frames as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1} & =3\mathbf{e}_{1}\\
\mathbf{e}_{1} & =\frac{1}{3}\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

We can easily represent the person's height relative to the two frames
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{h}^{1} & =6\mathbf{e}_{1}\\
\mathbf{h}^{2} & =2\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}$
\end_inset

 is the vector representing the person's height.
 Since the basis vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}$
\end_inset

 is geometrically 3 times larger than the basis vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

, as I transform the component of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}^{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{h}^{2}$
\end_inset

, the component needs to get three times smaller.
 To illustrate this better, suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 represents 1 foot and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}$
\end_inset

 represents 1 yard, then the person is 6 feet or 2 yards tall.
 As I convert between feet to yards, the component gets smaller, but my
 unit of measure gets bigger.
 Hopefully this explains why vector components are contravariant.
 If you are still confused, just sit down on a stump next to the path and
 reflect on what you have read.
 If you are still perplexed, I don't know what to say but good luck.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Active Transformation of a Vector
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:nonstandard_Active-Transformation-for"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An 
\series bold
active transformation
\series default
 is a transformation that maps the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 to a new orientation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}'$
\end_inset

 expressed in the same frame 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}=\left(O_{1},\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 as depicted in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Generic_VectorActive"

\end_inset

.
 In other words, an active transformation maps the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 to the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}'$
\end_inset

.
 There are many ways you can construct an active transformation.
 The method described here will help you build intuition for active transformati
ons in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{3}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/Nonstandard_VectorActive.pdf
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Generic_VectorActive"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To help us derive the active transformation, let's construct another frame
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}=\left(O_{2},\left\{ \mathbf{v},\mathbf{v}^{\perp}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 that has an orthogonal basis where each basis vector is the same length,
 and an origin that is coincident with the origin of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 These constraints leave two possible choices for the configurations of
 the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 One possible choice of this new construction is shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Generic_VectorActive_AngleAxis"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/Nonstandard_VectorActive_AngleAxis.pdf
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Generic_VectorActive_AngleAxis"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can construct the forward transformation that expresses the basis of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:Generic_AxisAngle"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbf{v} & =1\mathbf{e}_{1}+1\mathbf{e}_{2}\\
\mathbf{v}^{\perp} & =-\frac{7}{6}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\frac{5}{3}\mathbf{e}_{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

which can be represented in matrix notation as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{2}^{1}=\begin{bmatrix}1 & -\frac{7}{6}\\
1 & \frac{5}{3}
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
We have defined the basis vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 such that it meets the criteria 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{v}^{\perp}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \mathbf{v}^{\perp}\right\Vert =\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert $
\end_inset

.
 These two constrains allows us to write the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 as a function of the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 I won't get into this derivation, but know that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let's represent the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}'$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{v}'=\alpha^{1}\mathbf{v}+\alpha^{2}\mathbf{v}^{\perp}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The representation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}'$
\end_inset

 expressed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}' & =\left(\mathbf{v}'\cdot\mathbf{v}\right)\mathbf{v}+\left(\mathbf{v}'\cdot\mathbf{v}^{\perp}\right)\mathbf{v}^{\perp}\\
 & =-\frac{8}{17}\mathbf{v}+\frac{15}{17}\mathbf{v}^{\perp}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 Substituting in the forward transformation defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "sub:Generic_Forward-Transformation"

\end_inset

 yields 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}' & =-\frac{8}{17}\mathbf{v}+\frac{15}{17}\mathbf{v}^{\perp}\\
 & =-\frac{8}{17}\left(1\mathbf{e}_{1}+1\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)+\frac{15}{17}\left(-\frac{7}{6}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\frac{5}{3}\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\\
 & =\left(-\frac{8}{17}-\frac{35}{34}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(-\frac{8}{17}+\frac{75}{51}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}\\
 & =-1.5\mathbf{e}_{1}+1\mathbf{e}_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Honestly, the beauty of expressing the active transformation using this
 method cannot be fully appreciated until we move to standard frames which
 we will do next.
 The main take away from this subsection, is that an active transformation
 is a transformation between vectors in the same frame.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Transformations in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{2}$
\end_inset

 with Standard Reference Frames
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Well done brave adventurer! You have made it through the worst of it and
 will now be rewarded for a short season.
 At this point in the journey we will transition from talking about transformati
ons in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{2}$
\end_inset

 with arbitrary reference frames to standard reference frames.
 Standard reference frames can be used to simplify the derivation of the
 forward and backward transformations and passive and active transformations.
 To show this we will derive each transformation again.
 But that is not all! In this section we will also derive the directional
 derivative of the forward and backward transformations and conclude with
 the introduction of the Lie group 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Simplifications when using Standard Reference Frames
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Simplifications-when-using"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Up to this point we have worked with frames that have a nonorthonormal basis
 which can be difficult to work with.
 Using an orthonormal basis greatly simplifies finding the components of
 a vector relative to each basis vector.
 For example if I had a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{2}$
\end_inset

 , and I wanted to express it in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}=\left(O,\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbf{v} & =\alpha^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\alpha^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2},\label{eq:vectorComponentOrthonormal}
\end{align}

\end_inset

We can find the components by taking the inner product of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 with each basis vector of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 to form the system of equations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right) & =\alpha^{1}\left(\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)+\alpha^{2}\left(\mathbf{e}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\\
\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right) & =\alpha^{1}\left(\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)+\alpha^{2}\left(\mathbf{e}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which can be further reduced noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{e}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 since the basis vectors are orthogonal.
 Using this reduction we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right) & =\alpha^{1}\left(\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\\
\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right) & =\alpha^{2}\left(\mathbf{e}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which can be simplified even more noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)=\left(\mathbf{e}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)=1$
\end_inset

 since the basis vectors are unit length.
 Using this simplification we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right) & =\alpha^{1}\\
\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right) & =\alpha^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which allows us to rewrite 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:vectorComponentOrthonormal"

\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{v}=\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}
\]

\end_inset

which can also be expressed in terms of angles as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{v}=\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \cos\left(\theta_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \cos\left(\theta_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Even though there are two angles 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2}$
\end_inset

 in the above equation, the angles are related to each other.
 This relation can be discovered by taking the inner product of both sides
 of the equation with 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 to get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{v} & =\mathbf{v}\cdot\left(\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \cos\left(\theta_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \cos\left(\theta_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\\
 & =\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \left(\cos\left(\theta_{1}\right)\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)+\cos\left(\theta_{2}\right)\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\right)\\
 & =\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \left(\cos\left(\theta_{1}\right)\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \cos\left(\theta_{1}\right)+\cos\left(\theta_{2}\right)\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \cos\left(\theta_{2}\right)\right)\\
 & =\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert ^{2}\left(\cos^{2}\left(\theta_{1}\right)+\cos^{2}\left(\theta_{2}\right)\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which forces the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cos^{2}\left(\theta_{1}\right)+\cos^{2}\left(\theta_{2}\right)=1
\]

\end_inset

which implies 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\cos\left(\theta_{2}\right)=\pm\sin\left(\theta_{1}\right),
\]

\end_inset

where the sign can be determined by the sign of the inner product.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In summary, a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 can be expressed in a standard frame as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{v}=\alpha^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\alpha^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\alpha^{1} & =\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)=\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \cos\left(\theta_{1}\right),\\
\alpha^{2} & =\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)=\text{sign}\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\sin\left(\theta_{1}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

If 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is unit length, the equations simplify to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\alpha^{1} & =\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)=\cos\left(\theta_{1}\right)\\
\alpha^{2} & =\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)=\text{sign}\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\sin\left(\theta_{1}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 is in a higher dimensional space of dimension 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 being expressed in a standard frame we still have the identities
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\alpha^{i}=\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{i}\right)=\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \cos\left(\theta_{i}\right),\,i=\left\{ 1,\ldots,n\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

and the constraint 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum\left(\alpha^{i}\right)^{2}=\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert ,\,i=\left\{ 1,\ldots,n\right\} 
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Forward Transformation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:so2_Forward-Transformation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/SO2_ForwardBackward.pdf
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:FrameTransform2D"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}=\left(O_{1},\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}=\left(O_{2},\left\{ \mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1},\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 be standard frames with coincident origins in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{2}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 denoting the angle between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}$
\end_inset

 as depicted in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:FrameTransform2D"

\end_inset

.
 The forward transformation can be easily derived from the inner product
 using the simplifications discussed in subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Simplifications-when-using"

\end_inset

.
 Using these simplifications, the forward transformation is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1} & =\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\\
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2} & =\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

or in matrix notation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{2}^{1}=\begin{bmatrix}\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right) & \left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\\
\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right) & \left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can calculate the inner products between basis vectors as we have previously
 done.
 You should be a master at by now, so we won't review it again.
 Let's now express the inner products in terms of angles using what we learned
 from subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Inner-Product"

\end_inset

.
 The forward transformation expressed in terms of angles is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1} & =\left\Vert \mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\right\Vert \left\Vert \mathbf{e}_{1}\right\Vert \cos\left(\phi_{1,1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left\Vert \mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\right\Vert \left\Vert \mathbf{e}_{2}\right\Vert \cos\left(\phi_{1,2}\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\\
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2} & =\left\Vert \mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right\Vert \left\Vert \mathbf{e}_{1}\right\Vert \cos\left(\phi_{2,1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left\Vert \mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right\Vert \left\Vert \mathbf{e}_{2}\right\Vert \cos\left(\phi_{2,2}\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{a,b},\,a,b\in\left\{ 1,2\right\} $
\end_inset

 denotes the angle between vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{a}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{b}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the frames have an orthonormal basis, we can simplify the transformation
 to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1} & =\cos\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\mp\theta\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\\
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2} & =\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\pm\theta\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\cos\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the angle between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and the sign of each function 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\pm\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 is determined by the sign of the corresponding inner product as discussed
 in subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Simplifications-when-using"

\end_inset

.
 We can easily read off the sign of the inner products using figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:FrameTransform2D"

\end_inset

 to get
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1} & =\cos\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-\theta\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\\
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2} & =\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}+\theta\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\cos\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Using the identities 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}+\theta\right)=-\sin\left(\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}-\theta\right)=\sin\left(\theta\right)$
\end_inset

, the final forward transformation parametrized by 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:etilde_e"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1} & =\cos\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\sin\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\\
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2} & =-\sin\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\cos\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or in matrix notation we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{2}^{1}=\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(\theta\right) & -\sin\left(\theta\right)\\
\sin\left(\theta\right) & \cos\left(\theta\right)
\end{bmatrix},
\]

\end_inset

 where the superscript and subscript indicates that the forward transformation
 expresses the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
The angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 has not yet been used as a generalized coordinate.
 This is because 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 only describes the angle between the basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 For example the forward transformation for the frames shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:SO2_ForwardBackwardTheta"

\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{2}^{1}=\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(\theta\right) & \sin\left(\theta\right)\\
-\sin\left(\theta\right) & \cos\left(\theta\right)
\end{bmatrix},
\]

\end_inset

which cannot be determined by 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 alone and requires the sign of the inner products.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/SO2_ForwardBackwardTheta.pdf
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:SO2_ForwardBackwardTheta"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
Now, if we say that 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the angle measured from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}$
\end_inset

 such that a positive 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 denotes a counter-clockwise rotation from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is a generalized coordinate because I have given a reference for the coordinate
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 such that I can parametrize the forward transformation using only 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 When I use angles as generalized coordinates, I will specify it explicitly.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Backward Transformation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Backward-Transformation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a similar manner we can compute the backward transformation of the frames
 shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:FrameTransform2D"

\end_inset

.
 The backward transformation expresses the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 To construct the backward transformations we follow the same procedure
 as done in the previous subsection; however, we will skip a few steps here.
 We begin by relating each basis vector in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 to the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 using the inner product.
 This relation is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{e}_{1} & =\left(\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\\
\mathbf{e}_{2} & =\left(\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

or in matrix notation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B_{1}^{2}=\begin{bmatrix}\left(\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\right) & \left(\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\right)\\
\left(\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right) & \left(\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The backward transformation can also be expressed in terms of angles
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{e}_{1} & =\cos\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\pm\theta\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\\
\mathbf{e}_{2} & =\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\mp\theta\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+\cos\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the signs for 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\mp\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\pm\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 are determined from the inner product to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{e}_{1} & =\cos\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+-\sin\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\\
\mathbf{e}_{2} & =\sin\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+\cos\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which gives us the backward transformation in terms of the angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 The transformation can be represented using matrix notation as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B_{1}^{2}=\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(\theta\right) & \sin\left(\theta\right)\\
-\sin\left(\theta\right) & \cos\left(\theta\right)
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To verify the forward and backward transformations we must check that they
 are inverses of each other.
 It is easily verified that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
B_{1}^{2}F_{2}^{1} & =F_{2}^{1^{-1}}F_{2}^{1}\\
 & =F_{2}^{1^{\top}}F_{2}^{1}\\
 & =\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(\theta\right) & \sin\left(\theta\right)\\
-\sin\left(\theta\right) & \cos\left(\theta\right)
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(\theta\right) & -\sin\left(\theta\right)\\
\sin\left(\theta\right) & \cos\left(\theta\right)
\end{bmatrix}\\
 & =\begin{bmatrix}\cos^{2}\left(\theta\right)+\sin^{2}\left(\theta\right) & -\cos\left(\theta\right)\sin\left(\theta\right)+\cos\left(\theta\right)\sin\left(\theta\right)\\
\cos\left(\theta\right)\sin\left(\theta\right)-\cos\left(\theta\right)\sin\left(\theta\right) & \cos^{2}\left(\theta\right)+\sin^{2}\left(\theta\right)
\end{bmatrix}\\
 & =I
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{2}^{1^{-1}}=F_{2}^{1^{\top}}$
\end_inset

 means that the transformations are unitary.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
Now that I have given you several examples of how to determine the signs
 of the functions 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\mp\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\pm\theta\right)$
\end_inset

 using the inner product, I will skip this step in the future.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Passive Transformation of a Vector
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once again, the passive transformation of a vector is the transformation
 of components of a vector w.r.t.
 one frame to be w.r.t.
 another frame.
 We will follow the same procedure in subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Nonstandard_Passive-Transformation-of"

\end_inset

, and introduce the simplifications when using standard reference frames
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/SO2_VectorPassive.pdf
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:staticVector"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}=\left(O_{1},\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}=\left(O_{2},\left\{ \mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1},\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 be standard frames with coincident origins in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{2}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 denoting the angle between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 being an arbitrary vector as shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:staticVector"

\end_inset

, and suppose we express 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{v}=\alpha^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\alpha^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2},\label{eq:SO2_passiveVector}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

but we now wish to express it in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We can do this using the backward transformation calculated in subsection
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Backward-Transformation"

\end_inset

, which was 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{e}_{1} & =\cos\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+-\sin\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\\
\mathbf{e}_{2} & =\sin\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+\cos\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

or in matrix notation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
B_{1}^{2}=\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(\theta\right) & \sin\left(\theta\right)\\
-\sin\left(\theta\right) & \cos\left(\theta\right)
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Substituting the backward transformation into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SO2_passiveVector"

\end_inset

 yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v} & =\alpha^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\alpha^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2}\\
 & =\alpha^{1}\left(\cos\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+-\sin\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)+\alpha^{2}\left(\sin\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+\cos\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)\\
 & =\left(\alpha^{1}\cos\left(\theta\right)+\alpha^{2}\sin\left(\theta\right)\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+\left(-\alpha^{1}\sin\left(\theta\right)+\alpha^{2}\cos\left(\theta\right)\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which can be represented using matrix notation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}^{2} & =\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(\theta\right) & \sin\left(\theta\right)\\
-\sin\left(\theta\right) & \cos\left(\theta\right)
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\alpha^{1}\\
\alpha^{2}
\end{bmatrix}\\
 & =B_{1}^{2}\begin{bmatrix}\alpha^{1}\\
\alpha^{2}
\end{bmatrix}\\
 & =B\mathbf{v}^{1}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This should be so surprise after section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Nonstandard_Passive-Transformation-of"

\end_inset

.
 To inverse the process, you would simply use the inverse transformation
 which is the forward transformation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I purposely didn't calculate the components 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{2}$
\end_inset

 so that you could easily identify the components in the derivation.
 Just for fun and for more exposure let's calculate them in terms of an
 angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 which denotes the angle between the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v} & =\alpha^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\alpha^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2}\\
 & =\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}\\
 & =\left(\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \cos\left(\phi\right)\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \sin\left(\phi\right)\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Active Transformation of a Vector
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:SO2_Active-Transformation-of"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once again, an active transformation is a transformation that maps the vector
 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 to a new orientation 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}'$
\end_inset

 expressed in the same frame.
 We will use the same procedure as outlined in subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:nonstandard_Active-Transformation-for"

\end_inset

 and introduce the simplifications bestowed from using standard reference
 frames.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/SO2_ActiveGeometric.pdf
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:so2_ActiveGeometric"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}=\left(O_{1},\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 be a standard frame in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 a vector in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}'$
\end_inset

 the same vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 but transformed by the angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 denote the angle between the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Suppose we already know the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 relative to the frame 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v} & =\alpha^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\alpha^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2}\\
 & =\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}\\
 & =\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \cos\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \sin\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Our objective is to find the transformation that transforms the components
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 to the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}'$
\end_inset

.
 To do this, we will introduce another frame 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}=\left(O_{2},\left\{ \mathbf{v},\mathbf{v}^{\perp}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 whose origin is coincident with 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{1}$
\end_inset

, and whose basis vectors satisfy the constraints 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{v}^{\perp}=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert =\left\Vert \mathbf{v}^{\perp}\right\Vert $
\end_inset

.
 This new scenario is depicted in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:so2_ActiveGeometric2"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/SO2_ActiveGeometric2.pdf
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:so2_ActiveGeometric2"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can express the new basis vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}^{\perp} & =\beta^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\beta^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2}\\
 & =\left(\mathbf{v}^{\perp}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{v}^{\perp}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}\\
 & =-\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \sin\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \cos\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Note that the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{\perp}$
\end_inset

 can be written as a function of the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, i.e.,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}^{\perp} & =-\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}\\
 & =-\alpha^{2}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\alpha^{1}\mathbf{e}_{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can now form the forward transformation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v} & =\alpha^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\alpha^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2}\\
\mathbf{v}^{\perp} & =-\alpha^{2}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\alpha^{1}\mathbf{e}_{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In the next step we leave the expression of the forward transformation in
 terms of 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{2}$
\end_inset

 for clarity.
 We now express the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}'$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 in terms of the angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}' & =\left(\mathbf{v}'\cdot\frac{\mathbf{v}}{\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert }\right)\frac{\mathbf{v}}{\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert }+\left(\mathbf{v}'\cdot\frac{\mathbf{v}^{\perp}}{\left\Vert \mathbf{v}^{\perp}\right\Vert }\right)\frac{\mathbf{v}^{\perp}}{\left\Vert \mathbf{v}^{\perp}\right\Vert },
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the basis vectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 are normalized in order to treat it like a standard frame.
 The above expression is simplified to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}' & =\left(\left\Vert \mathbf{v}'\right\Vert \cos\left(\phi\right)\right)\frac{\mathbf{v}}{\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert }+\left(\left\Vert \mathbf{v}'\right\Vert \sin\left(\phi\right)\right)\frac{\mathbf{v}^{\perp}}{\left\Vert \mathbf{v}^{\perp}\right\Vert }\\
 & =\cos\left(\phi\right)\mathbf{v}+\sin\left(\phi\right)\mathbf{v}^{\perp}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Substituting in the forward transformation to express 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}'$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}' & =\cos\left(\phi\right)\mathbf{v}+\sin\left(\phi\right)\mathbf{v}^{\perp}\\
 & =\cos\left(\phi\right)\left(\alpha^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\alpha^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)+\sin\left(\phi\right)\left(-\alpha^{2}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\alpha^{1}\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\\
 & =\left(\cos\left(\phi\right)\alpha^{1}-\sin\left(\phi\right)\alpha^{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\sin\left(\phi\right)\alpha^{1}+\cos\left(\phi\right)\alpha^{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

or in matrix notation is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(\phi\right) & -\sin\left(\phi\right)\\
\sin\left(\phi\right) & \cos\left(\phi\right)
\end{bmatrix}}_{A}\begin{bmatrix}\alpha^{1}\\
\alpha^{2}
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the active transformation that transforms the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 to the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
You may notice that the transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 looks like a forward transformation, and you might be tempted to think
 of it as a forward transformation, but it isn't.
 They are fundamentally different and express two different things.
 A forward transformation is between frames, and an active transformation
 is between vectors expressed in the same frame.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
My dear fellow adventurer, I find it to be an appropriate time to discuss
 active transformations in the presence of coordinates.
 I only do this because you will come across it in other literature, and
 I want you to prepared to face it with full confidence and glory! Take
 this opportunity to notice the subtle differences.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}=\left(O_{1},\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 be a standard frame in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 a vector in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}'$
\end_inset

 the same vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 but rotated by the angle 
\begin_inset Formula $t\omega$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 be a generalized coordinate that denotes the angle from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 where a positive 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 denotes a counter-clockwise rotation, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 w.r.t.
 time, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 denote a time period as depicted in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:vectoryDynamics"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/VectorDynamic.pdf
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:vectoryDynamics"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once again the objective is to derive a transformation that maps the components
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 to the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}'$
\end_inset

.
 I will show you how to udo this using a different method than the one employed
 in the first part of this subsection.
 To begin we express the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v} & =\alpha^{1}\mathbf{e}_{1}+\alpha^{2}\mathbf{e}_{2}\\
 & =\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}\\
 & =\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \cos\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\mp\theta\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is a generalized coordinate, I do not need to look at the sign of the inner
 product 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 to determine the sign in the function 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\left(\frac{\pi}{2}\mp\theta\right)$
\end_inset

.
 I get it for free since 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is no longer ambiguous and is well defined.
 Thus 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{v}=\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \cos\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \sin\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At 
\begin_inset Formula $t>0$
\end_inset

 the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}'$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbf{v}' & =\left\Vert \mathbf{v}'\right\Vert \cos\left(\theta+t\omega\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left\Vert \mathbf{v}'\right\Vert \sin\left(\theta+t\omega\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}\label{eq:so2_active_angleAdd}\\
 & =\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \cos\left(\theta+t\omega\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \sin\left(\theta+t\omega\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}.\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset

Using trig identities, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}'$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 can be written as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}' & =\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \left(\cos\left(\theta\right)\cos\left(t\omega\right)-\sin\left(\theta\right)\sin\left(t\omega\right)\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \left(\sin\left(\theta\right)\cos\left(t\omega\right)+\cos\left(\theta\right)\sin\left(t\omega\right)\right)\mathbf{e}_{2},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and in matrix notation
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{v}'=\underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(t\omega\right) & -\sin\left(t\omega\right)\\
\sin\left(t\omega\right) & \cos\left(t\omega\right)
\end{bmatrix}}_{A}\underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \cos\left(\theta\right)\\
\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \sin\left(\theta\right)
\end{bmatrix}}_{\left(\alpha^{1},\alpha^{2}\right)}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the active transformation that transforms the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 to the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}'$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For many of you, this new method to derive the active transformation might
 seem more intuitive; however, I could only derive it this way since 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is a generalize coordinate which tells me how to add the angles 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t\omega$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:so2_active_angleAdd"

\end_inset

 without the use of inner products.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Concatenation of Transformations
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Concatenation-of-Transformations"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far we have only been working with two reference frames which is sufficient
 for some simple cases, but we need to be equipped with the means to handle
 many frames.
 By showing you how to construct the forward transformation between three
 standard frames, you will know how to construct the forward and backward
 transformations between any number of frames.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}=\left(O_{1},\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}=\left(O_{2},\left\{ \mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1},\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{3}=\left(O_{3},\left\{ \bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1},\mathbf{\bar{e}}_{2}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 be standard frames with coincident origins in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{2}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 denoting the angle between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 denoting the angle between 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}$
\end_inset

 as depicted in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:3frames_2d"

\end_inset

.
 Since we have three frames, we have multiple forward transformations.
 We will define the first forward transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{2}^{1}$
\end_inset

 as the transformation that expresses the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

, the second forward transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{3}^{2}$
\end_inset

 as the transformation that expresses the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{3}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

, and the third forward transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{3}^{1}$
\end_inset

 as the transformation that expresses the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{3}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/SO2_ForwardBackward_3.pdf
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:3frames_2d"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The first forward transformation is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1} & =\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\\
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2} & =\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

or in matrix notation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{2}^{1}=\begin{bmatrix}\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right) & \left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\\
\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right) & \left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The second forward transformation is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1} & =\left(\mathbf{\bar{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{\bar{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\\
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2} & =\left(\mathbf{\mathbf{\bar{e}}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{\mathbf{\bar{e}}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

or in matrix notation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{3}^{2}=\begin{bmatrix}\left(\mathbf{\bar{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\right) & \left(\mathbf{\mathbf{\bar{e}}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\right)\\
\left(\mathbf{\bar{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right) & \left(\mathbf{\mathbf{\bar{e}}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

The third forward transformation is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1} & =\left(\mathbf{\bar{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{\bar{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\\
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2} & =\left(\mathbf{\mathbf{\bar{e}}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{\mathbf{\bar{e}}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

or in matrix notation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{3}^{1}=\begin{bmatrix}\left(\mathbf{\bar{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right) & \left(\mathbf{\mathbf{\bar{e}}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\\
\left(\mathbf{\bar{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right) & \left(\mathbf{\mathbf{\bar{e}}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I know you are probably yawning at this point because you have seen this
 so many times, but restrain your yawn because we are now ready to derive
 the relationship between the forward transformations.
 We do this by substituting in the forward transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{3}^{2}$
\end_inset

 into the forward transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{3}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and they simplify using the properties of inner products.
 We first recall that the forward transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{3}^{1}$
\end_inset

 is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1} & =\left(\mathbf{\bar{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{\bar{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\\
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2} & =\left(\mathbf{\mathbf{\bar{e}}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{\mathbf{\bar{e}}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and then substitute 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{3}^{2}$
\end_inset

 into the inner products of 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{3}^{1}$
\end_inset

 to get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1} & =\left(\left(\left(\mathbf{\bar{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{\bar{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\left(\left(\mathbf{\bar{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{\bar{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\\
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2} & =\left(\left(\left(\mathbf{\mathbf{\bar{e}}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{\mathbf{\bar{e}}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\left(\left(\mathbf{\mathbf{\bar{e}}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{\mathbf{\bar{e}}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Distributing the inner product shows the relationship 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1} & =\left(\left(\mathbf{\bar{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\right)\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)+\left(\mathbf{\bar{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\left(\mathbf{\bar{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\right)\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)+\left(\mathbf{\bar{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\\
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2} & =\left(\left(\mathbf{\mathbf{\bar{e}}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\right)\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)+\left(\mathbf{\mathbf{\bar{e}}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\left(\mathbf{\mathbf{\bar{e}}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\right)\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)+\left(\mathbf{\mathbf{\bar{e}}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

or in matrix notation is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{3}^{1}=\begin{bmatrix}\left(\mathbf{\bar{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\right)\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)+\left(\mathbf{\bar{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right) & \left(\mathbf{\mathbf{\bar{e}}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\right)\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)+\left(\mathbf{\mathbf{\bar{e}}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\\
\left(\mathbf{\bar{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\right)\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)+\left(\mathbf{\bar{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right) & \left(\mathbf{\mathbf{\bar{e}}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\right)\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)+\left(\mathbf{\mathbf{\bar{e}}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

which can be factored out to be
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
F_{3}^{1} & =F_{2}^{1}F_{3}^{2}=\begin{bmatrix}\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right) & \left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\\
\left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right) & \left(\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\left(\mathbf{\bar{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\right) & \left(\mathbf{\mathbf{\bar{e}}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1}\right)\\
\left(\mathbf{\bar{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right) & \left(\mathbf{\mathbf{\bar{e}}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right)
\end{bmatrix}.\label{eq:SO2_threeTransformConvention}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note the order of operations when constructing 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{3}^{1}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{2}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{3}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This order of operation should help the notation make sense.
 When you multiply transformations together, the common superscripts and
 subscripts are crossed off, and the subscript and superscript that are
 not crossed off get carried over as shown below; 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{3}^{1}=F_{\cancel{2}}^{1}F_{3}^{\cancel{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

 This notation works with vectors.
 For example, let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{3}$
\end_inset

 denote the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 expressed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{1}$
\end_inset

 denote the same vector expressed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The notation for the transformation from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{3}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{v}^{1}=F_{3}^{1}\mathbf{v}^{3}
\]

\end_inset

or more expressively it is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}^{1} & =F_{2}^{1}F_{3}^{2}\mathbf{v}^{3}\\
 & =F_{2}^{1}\mathbf{v}^{2}\\
 & =\mathbf{v}^{1}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The forward transformations can also be represented using angles.
 I will not go through this derivation, but I will show you the end result
 for 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{3}^{1}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F_{3}^{1}=F_{3}^{2}F_{2}^{1}=\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(\phi\right) & -\sin\left(\phi\right)\\
\sin\left(\phi\right) & \cos\left(\phi\right)
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(\theta\right) & -\sin\left(\theta\right)\\
\sin\left(\theta\right) & \cos\left(\theta\right)
\end{bmatrix}.
\]

\end_inset

 An interesting thing you can see easily from this representations is that
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
F_{3}^{1} & =F_{3}^{2}F_{2}^{1}=F_{3}^{2}F_{2}^{1}\\
 & =\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(\theta\right) & -\sin\left(\theta\right)\\
\sin\left(\theta\right) & \cos\left(\theta\right)
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(\phi\right) & -\sin\left(\phi\right)\\
\sin\left(\phi\right) & \cos\left(\phi\right)
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which means that these types of transformations commute.
 This is not the case for higher dimensional transformations, and so to
 be consistent, I will only use the convention shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SO2_threeTransformConvention"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since we have the forward transformations, we already have the backward
 transformations.
 They are
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
B_{1}^{2} & =\left(F_{2}^{1}\right)^{-1}\\
B_{2}^{3} & =\left(F_{3}^{2}\right)^{-1}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
B_{1}^{3} & =\left(F_{3}^{1}\right)^{-1}\\
 & =\left(F_{2}^{1}F_{3}^{2}\right)^{-1}\\
 & =\left(F_{3}^{2}\right)^{-1}\left(F_{2}^{1}\right)^{-1}\\
 & =B_{2}^{3}B_{1}^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Note that when relating the backward transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}^{3}$
\end_inset

 to the backward transformations 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{3}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}^{2}$
\end_inset

, the order of operation is reversed.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Derivative of the Forward and Backward Transformations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far we have been working with static frames which is interesting, but
 limited.
 What if you have one frame rotating w.r.t.
 another frame and you want to how the transformation is changing? This
 is just the derivative of a transformation.
 To tackle this beastly problem we will utilize coordinates in order to
 perform calculus.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}=\left(O_{1},\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}=\left(O_{2},\left\{ \mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1},\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 be standard frames with coincident origins in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the generalized coordinate defined as the angle from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}$
\end_inset

 where a positive 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a counter-clockwise rotation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 is the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 denoting the angular velocity, and 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 denotes a time interval.
 This scenario is depicted in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:so2_derivative"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/SO(2)_derivative.pdf
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:so2_derivative"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We want to calculate the derivative of the transformation along 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

, this is done using the directional derivative.
 From subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:so2_Forward-Transformation"

\end_inset

 we know that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1} & =\cos\left(\theta+t\omega\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\sin\left(\theta+t\omega\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\\
\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2} & =-\sin\left(\theta+t\omega\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\cos\left(\theta+t\omega\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Using these equations, we can compute the directional derivative as follows
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:directionalDeriv2"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{d}{dt}\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1} & =\left.\frac{d}{dt}\left(\cos\left(\theta+t\omega\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\sin\left(\theta+t\omega\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\right|_{t=0}\\
\frac{d}{dt}\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2} & =\left.\frac{d}{dt}\left(-\sin\left(\theta+t\omega\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\cos\left(\theta+t\omega\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\right|_{t=0}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

evaluating this expression gives
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{d}{dt}\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1} & =-\omega\sin\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\omega\cos\left(\omega\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\\
\frac{d}{dt}\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2} & =-\omega\cos\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+-\omega\sin\left(\theta\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which can be represented in matrix notation as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{d}{dt}F_{2}^{1} & =\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(\theta\right) & -\sin\left(\theta\right)\\
\sin\left(\theta\right) & \cos\left(\theta\right)
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}0 & -\omega\\
\omega & 0
\end{bmatrix}\\
 & =F_{2}^{1}\begin{bmatrix}0 & -\omega\\
\omega & 0
\end{bmatrix}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

The derivative of the backwards transformation can be shown to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{d}{dt}B_{1}^{2} & =\begin{bmatrix}0 & \omega\\
-\omega & 0
\end{bmatrix}B_{1}^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The derivative of the transformation can be expressed differently which
 will be helpful later on.
 We begin with 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:directionalDeriv2"

\end_inset

 and separate the terms out to get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{d}{dt}\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1} & =\frac{d}{dt}\left.\left[\left(\cos\left(t\omega\right)\cos\left(\theta\right)-\sin\left(t\omega\right)\sin\left(\theta\right)\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\cos\left(t\omega\right)\sin\left(\theta\right)+\sin\left(t\omega\right)\cos\left(\theta\right)\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right]\right|_{t=0}\\
\frac{d}{dt}\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2} & =\frac{d}{dt}\left.\left[\left(-\sin\left(t\omega\right)\cos\left(\theta\right)-\cos\left(t\omega\right)\sin\left(\theta\right)\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(-\sin\left(t\omega\right)\sin\left(\theta\right)+\cos\left(t\omega\right)\cos\left(\theta\right)\right)\mathbf{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right]\right|_{t=0}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which can be represented in matrix form 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{d}{dt}\left.\left(\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(\theta\right) & -\sin\left(\theta\right)\\
\sin\left(\theta\right) & \cos\left(\theta\right)
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(t\omega\right) & -\sin\left(t\omega\right)\\
\sin\left(t\omega\right) & \cos\left(t\omega\right)
\end{bmatrix}\right)\right|_{t=0}
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 doesn't depend on time, we can write the derivative as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(\theta\right) & -\sin\left(\theta\right)\\
\sin\left(\theta\right) & \cos\left(\theta\right)
\end{bmatrix}\left(\frac{d}{dt}\left.\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(t\omega\right) & -\sin\left(t\omega\right)\\
\sin\left(t\omega\right) & \cos\left(t\omega\right)
\end{bmatrix}\right|_{t=0}\right).
\]

\end_inset

Evaluating the expression yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(\theta\right) & -\sin\left(\theta\right)\\
\sin\left(\theta\right) & \cos\left(\theta\right)
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}0 & -\omega\\
\omega & 0
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

which is the same result as above.
 However, this matrix representation allows us to represent the change in
 the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega$
\end_inset

 as a transformation between frames.
 This idea will come into play when finding the derivatives of transformations
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
SO
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is time for my confession.
 I haven't been telling you everything.
 The transformations that we have been discussing in this section are rotation
 matrices that belong to a group called the special orthogonal group of
 2-dimensions denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(2\right)\coloneqq\left\{ R\in\mathbb{R}^{2\times2}|R^{\top}R=I,\,\text{det}\left(R\right)=1\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 This means that forward transformations can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{2}^{1}=F_{2}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and backward transformations can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{1}^{2}=B_{1}^{2}$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{1}^{2}R_{2}^{1}=I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(R_{1}^{2}\right)^{\top}=R_{2}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 As a side note, all of the transformations that we have worked with have
 belonged to the general linear group of 2-dimensions.
 The definition of a group is
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
A 
\series bold
group 
\series default

\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a set of elements combined with an operation 
\begin_inset Formula $\bullet$
\end_inset

 with the following properties
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Closure
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
For all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b\in G$
\end_inset

, the result of the operation 
\begin_inset Formula $a\bullet b\in G$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Associativity
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
For all 
\begin_inset Formula $a,\,b$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 in G, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(a\bullet b\right)\bullet c=a\bullet\left(b\bullet c\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Identity Element
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
There exists an element 
\begin_inset Formula $e\in G$
\end_inset

 that for all 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in G$
\end_inset

, the equation 
\begin_inset Formula $e\bullet a=a\bullet e=a$
\end_inset

 holds.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Inverse Element
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
For each 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in G$
\end_inset

 there exists an element 
\begin_inset Formula $b\in G$
\end_inset

, such that 
\begin_inset Formula $a\bullet b=b\bullet a=e$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

 is the identity element.
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
The set of elements in 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

 is the set of all the matrices 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 such that 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{\top}R=I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{det}\left(R\right)=1$
\end_inset

, and the operation of 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

 is the matrix multiplication.
 In the next section, we will be working with the group 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

 which is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(3\right)\coloneqq\left\{ R\in\mathbb{R}^{3\times3}|R^{\top}R=I,\,\text{det}\left(R\right)=1\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Rotation matrices have the unique property that they preserver length,
 i.e., the inner product of the vector components do not change as they change
 basis.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Rotation Matrices in 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(3\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Every physical system inherently resides in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Depending on what the system is, we can sometimes constrain it to reside
 in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{1}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In the case that the physical system is 1-dimensional, there is no orientation
 or need for a rotation matrix.
 In the case the physical system is 2-dimensional, it has orientation that
 can be represented using rotation matrices of 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

.
 In the case that the physical system is 3-dimensional, we represent the
 orientation using rotation matrices of 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section we will discuss the forward and backward transformations
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

, active and passive rotations of vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{3}$
\end_inset

, embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

, and the derivative of the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

.
 The pace will be a little fast because by now you should be familiar with
 the material.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Forward and Backward Transformation
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:SO3_Forward-and-Backward"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}=\left(O_{1},\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2},\mathbf{e}_{3}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}=\left(O_{2},\left\{ \tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1},\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2},\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 be standard frames with coincident origins in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{3}$
\end_inset

 as depicted in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:SO3_changeBasis"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/SO3_changeOfBasis.pdf
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:SO3_changeBasis"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The forward transformation is defined using the inner product
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1} & =\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}\\
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2} & =\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}\\
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3} & =\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and in matrix notation we get
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
R_{2}^{1} & =\begin{bmatrix}\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right) & \left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right) & \left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\\
\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right) & \left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right) & \left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\\
\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right) & \left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right) & \left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Once we have the forward transformation, we can easily extract the backward
 transformation to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{1}^{2}=\left(R_{2}^{1}\right)^{\top}.
\]

\end_inset

I am not using the previous notation 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 to denote the forward and backward transformations so that you can get
 use to them being denoted as 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can also represent the transformations using angles between basis vectors
 like we did with 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

 and get something like 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{2}^{1}=\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(\theta_{1,1}\right) & \cos\left(\theta_{2,1}\right) & \cos\left(\theta_{3,1}\right)\\
\cos\left(\theta_{1,2}\right) & \cos\left(\theta_{2,2}\right) & \cos\left(\theta_{3,2}\right)\\
\cos\left(\theta_{1,3}\right) & \cos\left(\theta_{2,3}\right) & \cos\left(\theta_{3,3}\right)
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i,j},\,i\in\left\{ 1,2,3\right\} $
\end_inset

 is the angle between the basis vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{j},\,i,j\in\left\{ 1,2,3\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Unlike 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

, the elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

 cannot be parameterized with one coordinate.
 This is due to the fact that 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

 has three degrees of freedom even though it has 9 variables.
 This reduction comes from the constraints derived from the properties 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{\top}R=I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\text{det}\left(R\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 These constraints are 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
a_{11}^{2}+a_{12}^{2}+a_{13}^{2} & =1\\
a_{21}^{2}+a_{22}^{2}+a_{23}^{2} & =1\\
a_{31}^{2}+a_{32}^{2}+a_{33}^{2} & =1\\
a_{11}a_{21}+a_{12}a_{22}+a_{13}a_{23} & =0\\
a_{11}a_{31}+a_{12}a_{32}+a_{13}a_{33} & =0\\
a_{21}a_{31}+a_{22}a_{32}+a_{23}a_{33} & =0\\
\det\left(R\right) & =1
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i,j}=\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{i}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{j}\right),\,i,j\in\left\{ 1,2,3\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 The first 6 constraints ensures that the transformation is an element of
 the orthogonal group of three dimensions denotes as 
\begin_inset Formula $O\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

, and the last constraint ensures that it is an element of 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Even with these constraints, it is not easy to parameterize elements of
 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

 using only three generalize coordinates.
 For this reason, it is best to leave it in its original definition of inner
 products and angles without any simplification.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are methods that can be used to construct a rotation matrix such as
 axis-angle, Euler angles, Rodriguez parameterization, etc.
 However, these other forms of attitude representation are not diffeomorphic
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

, and so care needs to be taken when using these other forms.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Passive Rotations of Vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{3}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/SO3_PassiveRotation.pdf
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:SO3_PassiveRotation"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}=\left(O_{1},\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2},\mathbf{e}_{3}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}=\left(O_{2},\left\{ \tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1},\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2},\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 be standard frames with coincident origins in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{3}$
\end_inset

 and vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 be a vector in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{3}$
\end_inset

 as depicted in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:SO3_PassiveRotation"

\end_inset

.
 We can express the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{v}=\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}.
\]

\end_inset

Using the backward transformation defined in subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:SO3_Forward-and-Backward"

\end_inset

, we can transform the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 to be expressed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 as follows
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v} & =\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}\\
 & =\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\left(\left(\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right)\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}+\left(\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right)\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right)\\
 & +\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\left(\left(\mathbf{e}_{2}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right)\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{e}_{2}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}+\left(\mathbf{e}_{2}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right)\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right)\\
 & +\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\left(\left(\mathbf{e}_{3}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right)\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}+\left(\mathbf{e}_{3}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}+\left(\mathbf{e}_{3}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right)\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which can be simplified and represented using matrix notation as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{v}=\underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}\left(\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right) & \left(\mathbf{e}_{2}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right) & \left(\mathbf{e}_{3}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right)\\
\left(\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right) & \left(\mathbf{e}_{2}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right) & \left(\mathbf{e}_{3}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\\
\left(\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right) & \left(\mathbf{e}_{2}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right) & \left(\mathbf{e}_{3}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right)
\end{bmatrix}}_{R_{1}^{2}}\underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\\
\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\\
\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)
\end{bmatrix}}_{\alpha}.
\]

\end_inset

where the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{1}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is the backward transformation and the matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 contains the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 expressed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Once again we see that the components of a vector transform contravariantly
 to the basis vectors.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Active Rotations of Vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{3}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The derivation of this rotation is somewhat intense, but I tried by best
 to prepare you for it in subsections 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:nonstandard_Active-Transformation-for"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:SO2_Active-Transformation-of"

\end_inset

.
 Hopefully these subsections will help us bare this section with a little
 more ease.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/SO3_ActiveRotations.pdf
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:SO3_VectorActive"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}=\left(O_{1},\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2},\mathbf{e}_{3}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 be a standard frame in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{3}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 , 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 denote vectors in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 The vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}'$
\end_inset

 denotes the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 after a rotation about the unit vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 by the generalize coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 which is positive if the rotation about 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 is counter-clockwise.
 We have also constructed two additional 
\emph on
non-standard 
\emph default
frames 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}=\left(O_{1},\left\{ \mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{1},\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2},\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{3}=\left(O_{3},\left\{ \bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1},\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2},\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 whose origins are coincident with 
\begin_inset Formula $O_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 We define the basis vectors of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{3}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3} & =\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}=\mathbf{n},\\
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2} & =\mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}',\\
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1} & =-\mathbf{n}\times\left(\mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}'\right),\\
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2} & =\mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}',\\
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1} & =-\mathbf{n}\times\left(\mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\left\Vert \bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right\Vert  & =\left\Vert \tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right\Vert =1,\\
\left\Vert \bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right\Vert  & =\left\Vert \mathbf{v}'\right\Vert \sin\left(\phi\right),\\
\left\Vert \bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right\Vert  & =\left\Vert \mathbf{v}'\right\Vert \sin\left(\phi\right),\\
\left\Vert \tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right\Vert  & =\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \sin\left(\phi\right),\\
\left\Vert \tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right\Vert  & =\left\Vert \mathbf{v}\right\Vert \sin\left(\phi\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

with 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi$
\end_inset

 being the angle between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 which is the same angle between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 resides in the plane spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{3}$
\end_inset

 and the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}'$
\end_inset

 resides in the plane spanned by 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 In fact we have that 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbf{v} & =\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{n}\right)\mathbf{n}-\mathbf{n}\times\left(\mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right)\\
 & =\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right)\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}+\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\label{eq:SO3_active_vid}
\end{align}

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbf{v}' & =\left(\mathbf{v}'\cdot\mathbf{n}\right)\mathbf{n}-\mathbf{n}\times\left(\mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}'\right).\\
 & =\left(\mathbf{v}'\cdot\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right)\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3}+\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}.
\end{align}

\end_inset

We also note the following identities 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:SO_Active_Identities"

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right) & =\left(\mathbf{v}'\cdot\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right)\\
\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right) & =\left(\mathbf{v}'\cdot\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\\
\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right) & =\left(\mathbf{v}'\cdot\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right)\\
\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{v}\right) & =\left(\mathbf{v}'\cdot\mathbf{v}'\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)=\left(\mathbf{v}'\cdot\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Take a moment to really convince yourself of everything presented to you
 so far in this subsection; otherwise, you will get lost.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Recall that the objective of an active transformation is to transform the
 components of a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 to the components of the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}'$
\end_inset

 expressed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 To do this, we will use the frames 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{3}$
\end_inset

 to simplify the derivation.
 We will assume that we already have expressed 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=\sum_{i=1}^{3}\alpha^{i}\mathbf{e}_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Now let's derive the transformation!
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's first construct the forward transformation that expresses the basis
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{3}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 as such 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1} & =\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right)\frac{\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}}{\left\Vert \mathbf{\tilde{\mathbf{e}}}_{1}\right\Vert ^{2}}+\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\frac{\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}}{\left\Vert \mathbf{\tilde{\mathbf{e}}}_{2}\right\Vert ^{2}}+\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right)\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\\
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2} & =\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right)\frac{\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}}{\left\Vert \mathbf{\tilde{\mathbf{e}}}_{1}\right\Vert ^{2}}+\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\frac{\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}}{\left\Vert \mathbf{\tilde{\mathbf{e}}}_{2}\right\Vert ^{2}}+\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right)\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\\
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3} & =\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right)\frac{\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}}{\left\Vert \mathbf{\tilde{\mathbf{e}}}_{1}\right\Vert ^{2}}+\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\frac{\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}}{\left\Vert \mathbf{\tilde{\mathbf{e}}}_{2}\right\Vert ^{2}}+\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right)\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which can be simplified to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1} & =\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right)\frac{\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}}{\left\Vert \mathbf{\tilde{\mathbf{e}}}_{1}\right\Vert ^{2}}+\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\frac{\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}}{\left\Vert \mathbf{\tilde{\mathbf{e}}}_{2}\right\Vert ^{2}}\\
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2} & =\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right)\frac{\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}}{\left\Vert \mathbf{\tilde{\mathbf{e}}}_{1}\right\Vert ^{2}}+\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\frac{\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}}{\left\Vert \mathbf{\tilde{\mathbf{e}}}_{2}\right\Vert ^{2}}\\
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3} & =\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

since 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right)=\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right)=1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now let's express 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}'$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{3}$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{v}'=\left(\mathbf{v}'\cdot\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right)\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3}+\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}.
\]

\end_inset

Using the identities in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SO_Active_Identities"

\end_inset

 we can express 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}'$
\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{v}'=\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{n}\right)\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3}+\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}.
\]

\end_inset

Substituting in the forward transformation yields
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{v}'=\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{n}\right)\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}+\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right)\frac{\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}}{\left\Vert \mathbf{\tilde{\mathbf{e}}}_{1}\right\Vert ^{2}}+\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\frac{\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}}{\left\Vert \mathbf{\tilde{\mathbf{e}}}_{2}\right\Vert ^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

which can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{v}'=\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{n}\right)\mathbf{n}+\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right)\frac{-\mathbf{n}\times\left(\mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right)}{\left\Vert \mathbf{n}\times\left(\mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right)\right\Vert ^{2}}+\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\frac{\left(\mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right)}{\left\Vert \mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right\Vert ^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

Using the relation in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:SO3_active_vid"

\end_inset

 allows us to write the above equation as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{v}'=\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{n}\right)\mathbf{n}+\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right)\frac{\left(\mathbf{v}-\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{n}\right)\mathbf{n}\right)}{\left\Vert \mathbf{n}\times\left(\mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right)\right\Vert ^{2}}+\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\frac{\left(\mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right)}{\left\Vert \mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right\Vert ^{2}}
\]

\end_inset

which can be rewritten as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{v}'=\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{n}\right)\mathbf{n}\left(1-\frac{\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right)}{\left\Vert \mathbf{n}\times\left(\mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right)\right\Vert ^{2}}\right)+\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right)\frac{\mathbf{v}}{\left\Vert \mathbf{n}\times\left(\mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right)\right\Vert ^{2}}+\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\frac{\left(\mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right)}{\left\Vert \mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right\Vert ^{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

which can be expressed in terms of angles
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}' & =\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{n}\right)\mathbf{n}\left(1-\frac{\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right)}{\left\Vert \mathbf{n}\times\left(\mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right)\right\Vert ^{2}}\right)+\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right)\frac{\mathbf{v}}{\left\Vert \mathbf{n}\times\left(\mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right)\right\Vert ^{2}}+\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\frac{\left(\mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right)}{\left\Vert \mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right\Vert ^{2}}\\
 & =\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{n}\right)\mathbf{n}\left(1-\frac{\left\Vert \mathbf{n}\times\left(\mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right)\right\Vert ^{2}\cos\left(\psi_{1}\right)}{\left\Vert \mathbf{n}\times\left(\mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right)\right\Vert ^{2}}\right)+\frac{\mathbf{v}\left\Vert \mathbf{n}\times\left(\mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right)\right\Vert ^{2}\cos\left(\psi_{1}\right)}{\left\Vert \mathbf{n}\times\left(\mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right)\right\Vert ^{2}}+\left\Vert \mathbf{n}\times\left(\mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right)\right\Vert \left\Vert \mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right\Vert \cos\left(\psi_{2}\right)\frac{\left(\mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right)}{\left\Vert \mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right\Vert ^{2}}\\
 & =\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{n}\right)\mathbf{n}\left(1-\cos\left(\psi_{1}\right)\right)+\mathbf{v}\cos\left(\psi_{1}\right)+\cos\left(\psi_{2}\right)\left(\mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{1}$
\end_inset

 is the angle between 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the angle between 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that we have not used any generalized coordinates yet.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If we use the generalized coordinate 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

, we can express the transformation as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\mathbf{v}' & =\left(\mathbf{v}\cdot\mathbf{n}\right)\mathbf{n}\left(1-\cos\left(\theta\right)\right)+\mathbf{v}\cos\left(\theta\right)+\sin\left(\theta\right)\left(\mathbf{n}\times\mathbf{v}\right)\label{eq:Rodrigues_rotation_formula}
\end{align}

\end_inset

which is the Rodrigues rotation formula for rotating a vector by angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 about the unit vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
 This equation might seem fearsome, but remember that if the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

 are represented in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

, then they can be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v} & =\sum_{i=1}^{3}\alpha^{i}\mathbf{e}_{i}\\
\mathbf{n} & =\sum_{i=1}^{3}\beta^{i}\mathbf{e}_{i}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

or in matrix notation
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v} & =\underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}\alpha^{1}\\
\alpha^{2}\\
\alpha^{2}
\end{bmatrix}}_{A}\\
\mathbf{n} & =\underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}\beta^{1}\\
\beta^{2}\\
\beta^{3}
\end{bmatrix}}_{B}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which allows us to write the Rodrigues rotation formula in matrix form as
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\mathbf{v}'=\left(A\cdot B\right)B\left(1-\cos\left(\theta\right)\right)+A\cos\left(\theta\right)+\sin\left(\theta\right)\left[B\right]_{\times}A\label{eq:rodrigues_component}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[B\right]_{\times}$
\end_inset

 is the skew symmetric matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(A\cdot B\right)=\sum_{i=1}^{3}\alpha^{i}\beta^{i}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Remember that the objective was to form a rotation matrix to transform the
 components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 to the components of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}'$
\end_inset

, which we have not done.
 To do this, we will use the identity 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left(A\cdot B\right)B\left(1-\cos\left(\theta\right)\right)+A\cos\left(\theta\right)=\left(I+\left[B\right]_{\times}^{2}\left(1-\cos\left(\theta\right)\right)\right)A
\]

\end_inset

to write 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:rodrigues_component"

\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{v}' & =\left(I+\left[B\right]_{\times}^{2}\left(1-\cos\left(\theta\right)\right)\right)A+\sin\left(\theta\right)\left[B\right]_{\times}A\\
 & =\left(I+\sin\left(\theta\right)\left[B\right]_{\times}+\left[B\right]_{\times}^{2}\left(1-\cos\left(\theta\right)\right)\right)A\\
 & =RA
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where the rotation matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $R=\left(I+\sin\left(\theta\right)\left[B\right]_{\times}+\left[B\right]_{\times}^{2}\left(1-\cos\left(\theta\right)\right)\right)=\exp\left(\theta\left[B\right]_{\times}\right)$
\end_inset

.
 This identity would make more sense with an understanding of the Lie algebra
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

, but that is beyond the scope of this document.
 Let it suffice that we have constructed an active rotation matrix from
 the Rodrigues rotation formula to rotate a vector by angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 about a unit vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{n}$
\end_inset

.
 There are other methods to construct an active rotation matrix, but this
 one is used extensively in robotics and is good to understand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
This active rotation matrix could have been derived purely from a geometric
 perspective instead of using the generalized coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 if we kept track of the signs of 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\left(\psi_{1}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\left(\psi_{2}\right)$
\end_inset

 using the signs of their corresponding inner product.
 I didn't do that here because the Rodrigues rotation formula is typically
 used with a generalized coordinate that denotes the angle of rotation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout --Separator--

\end_layout

\begin_layout Remark
The Rodrigues rotation formula, also known as axis-angle, can also be used
 to represent a forward and backward transformation instead of using rotation
 matrices; however, the axis-angle representation is not diffeomorphic to
 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

 and contains singularities.
 This is why I suggest not using the axis-angle representation to represent
 forward and backward transformations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Embedding SO
\begin_inset Formula $\left(2\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/Rotation_e1.pdf
	width 30col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:rotation_e1"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/Rotation_e2.pdf
	width 30col%

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:rotation_e2"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align right
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/Rotation_e3.pdf
	width 30col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:rotation_e3"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A simplified definition of embedding is the act of immersing a space inside
 of another space such that all of it's structure is preserved.
 A simple example of this is embedding 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}\coloneqq\left\{ \left(x,y\right)|x\in\mathbb{R},\,y\in\mathbb{R}\right\} $
\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{3}\coloneqq\left\{ \left(\left(x,y\right),z\right)|\left(x,y\right)\in\mathbb{R}^{2},\,z=c\in\mathbb{R}\right\} $
\end_inset

, which preserves all of it's structure.
 In a similar manner, 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

 can be embedded into 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

.
 There are an infinite number of ways to do this.
 I will only address the more common ones which are shown in figures 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:rotation_e1"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:rotation_e2"

\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:rotation_e3"

\end_inset

.
 These figures describe a rotation about a basis vector of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}=\left(O_{1},\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2},\mathbf{e}_{3}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{i},\,i\in\left\{ 1,2,3\right\} $
\end_inset

 to get to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}=\left(O_{2},\left\{ \tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1},\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2},\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's derive the forward transformations for each scenario depicted in the
 figures.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:rotation_e1"

\end_inset

 shows a rotation about 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 by angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{e}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{j}=\mathbf{e}_{i}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}=0,\,i,j\in\left\{ 2,3\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

These constraints allows us to reduce the forward transformation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1} & =\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}\\
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2} & =\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}\\
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3} & =\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1} & =1\mathbf{e}_{1}+0\mathbf{e}_{2}+0\mathbf{e}_{3}\\
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2} & =0\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}\\
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3} & =0\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and we can represent the inner products as angles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1} & =1\mathbf{e}_{1}+0\mathbf{e}_{2}+0\mathbf{e}_{2}\\
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2} & =0\mathbf{e}_{1}+\cos\left(\theta_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+\sin\left(\theta_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}\\
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3} & =0\mathbf{e}_{1}-\sin\left(\theta_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+\cos\left(\theta_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which in matrix notation is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{2}^{1}=\begin{bmatrix}1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \cos\left(\theta_{1}\right) & -\sin\left(\theta_{1}\right)\\
0 & \sin\left(\theta_{1}\right) & \cos\left(\theta_{1}\right)
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:rotation_e2"

\end_inset

 shows a rotation about 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{2}$
\end_inset

 by angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{2}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{e}_{2}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{j}=\mathbf{e}_{i}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}=0,\,i,j\in\left\{ 1,3\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

These constraints allows us to reduce the forward transformation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1} & =\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}\\
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2} & =\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}\\
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3} & =\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1} & =\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+0\mathbf{e}_{2}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}\\
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2} & =0\mathbf{e}_{1}+1\mathbf{e}_{2}+0\mathbf{e}_{3}\\
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3} & =\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+0\mathbf{e}_{2}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and we can represent the inner products as angles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1} & =\cos\left(\theta_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+0\mathbf{e}_{2}-\sin\left(\theta_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}\\
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2} & =0\mathbf{e}_{1}+1\mathbf{e}_{2}+0\mathbf{e}_{3}\\
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3} & =\sin\left(\theta_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+0\mathbf{e}_{2}+\cos\left(\theta_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which in matrix notation is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{2}^{1}=\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(\theta_{2}\right) & 0 & \sin\left(\theta_{2}\right)\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
-\sin\left(\theta_{2}\right) & 0 & \cos\left(\theta_{2}\right)
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:rotation_e3"

\end_inset

 shows a rotation about 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{3}$
\end_inset

 by angle 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 This implies that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{3}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathbf{e}_{3}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{j}=\mathbf{e}_{i}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}=0,\,i,j\in\left\{ 1,2\right\} 
\]

\end_inset

These constraints allows us to reduce the forward transformation 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1} & =\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}\\
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2} & =\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}\\
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3} & =\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

to
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1} & =\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+0\mathbf{e}_{3}\\
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2} & =\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+0\mathbf{e}_{3}\\
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3} & =0\mathbf{e}_{1}+0\mathbf{e}_{2}+1\mathbf{e}_{3}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

and we can represent the inner products as angles
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1} & =\cos\left(\theta_{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\sin\left(\theta_{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+0\mathbf{e}_{3}\\
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2} & =-\sin\left(\theta_{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\cos\left(\theta_{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+0\mathbf{e}_{3}\\
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3} & =0\mathbf{e}_{1}+0\mathbf{e}_{2}+1\mathbf{e}_{3}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

which in matrix notation is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{2}^{1}=\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(\theta_{3}\right) & -\sin\left(\theta_{3}\right) & 0\\
\sin\left(\theta_{3}\right) & \cos\left(\theta_{3}\right) & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These embeddings are used extensively.
 One such example is with Euler-angles which I will not get into.
 We will use these embeddings to derive the derivative of elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

 later on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Concatenations of Rotations
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}=\left(O_{1},\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2},\mathbf{e}_{3}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}=\left(O_{2},\left\{ \tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1},\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2},\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{3}=\left(O_{3},\left\{ \bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1},\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2},\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 be standard frames with coincident origins in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{3}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}$
\end_inset

 being the angle of rotation between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 about 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2}$
\end_inset

 being the angle of rotation between 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{3}$
\end_inset

 about 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}$
\end_inset

 as depicted in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:so3_concatenate"

\end_inset

.
 If we have two forward transformations that express the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{3}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

, we can concatenate them to express the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{3}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/SO3_concatenate.pdf
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:so3_concatenate"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We begin with a geometric derivation to show to concatenate two rotations.
 To do this we construct the forward transformation that expresses the basis
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:SO3_concatenate_F1"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1} & =\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}\\
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2} & =\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}\\
\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3} & =\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 or in matrix notation is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{2}^{1}=\begin{bmatrix}\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right) & \left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right) & \left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\\
\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right) & \left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right) & \left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\\
\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right) & \left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right) & \left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and the forward transformation that expresses the bases of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{3}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "eq:SO3_concatenate_F2"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1} & =\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right)\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}+\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}+\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right)\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\\
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2} & =\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right)\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}+\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}+\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right)\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\\
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3} & =\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right)\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}+\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}+\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right)\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 or in matrix notation is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{3}^{2}=\begin{bmatrix}\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right) & \left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right) & \left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right)\\
\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right) & \left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right) & \left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\\
\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right) & \left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right) & \left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right)
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can substitute 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SO3_concatenate_F1"

\end_inset

 into 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:SO3_concatenate_F2"

\end_inset

 to get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1} & =a_{11}\left(b_{11}\mathbf{e}_{1}+b_{12}\mathbf{e}_{2}+b_{13}\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)+a_{12}\left(b_{21}\mathbf{e}_{1}+b_{22}\mathbf{e}_{2}+b_{23}\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)+a_{13}\left(b_{31}\mathbf{e}_{1}+b_{32}\mathbf{e}_{2}+b_{33}\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\\
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2} & =a_{21}\left(b_{11}\mathbf{e}_{1}+b_{12}\mathbf{e}_{2}+b_{13}\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)+a_{22}\left(b_{21}\mathbf{e}_{1}+b_{22}\mathbf{e}_{2}+b_{23}\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)+a_{23}\left(b_{31}\mathbf{e}_{1}+b_{32}\mathbf{e}_{2}+b_{33}\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)\\
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3} & =a_{31}\left(b_{11}\mathbf{e}_{1}+b_{12}\mathbf{e}_{2}+b_{13}\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)+a_{32}\left(b_{21}\mathbf{e}_{1}+b_{22}\mathbf{e}_{2}+b_{23}\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)+a_{33}\left(b_{31}\mathbf{e}_{1}+b_{32}\mathbf{e}_{2}+b_{33}\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{ij}\coloneqq\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{i}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{j}\right),\,i,j\left\{ 1,2,3\right\} $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{ij}\coloneqq\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right),\,i,j\in\left\{ 1,2,3\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Rearranging the terms in the equation above yields
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1} & =\left(a_{11}b_{11}+a_{12}b_{21}+a_{13}b_{31}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(a_{11}b_{12}+a_{12}b_{22}+a_{13}b_{32}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+\left(a_{11}b_{13}+a_{12}b_{23}+a_{13}b_{33}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}\\
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2} & =\left(a_{21}b_{11}+a_{22}b_{21}+a_{23}b_{31}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(a_{21}b_{12}+a_{22}b_{22}+a_{23}b_{32}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+\left(a_{21}b_{13}+a_{22}b_{23}+a_{23}b_{33}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}\\
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3} & =\left(a_{31}b_{11}+a_{32}b_{21}+a_{33}b_{31}\right)\mathbf{e}_{1}+\left(a_{31}b_{12}+a_{32}b_{22}+a_{33}b_{32}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+\left(a_{31}b_{13}+a_{32}b_{23}+a_{33}b_{33}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

or in matrix form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{3}^{1}=\begin{bmatrix}\left(a_{11}b_{11}+a_{12}b_{21}+a_{13}b_{31}\right) & \left(a_{21}b_{11}+a_{22}b_{21}+a_{23}b_{31}\right) & \left(a_{31}b_{11}+a_{32}b_{21}+a_{33}b_{31}\right)\\
\left(a_{11}b_{12}+a_{12}b_{22}+a_{13}b_{32}\right) & \left(a_{21}b_{12}+a_{22}b_{22}+a_{23}b_{32}\right) & \left(a_{31}b_{12}+a_{32}b_{22}+a_{33}b_{32}\right)\\
\left(a_{11}b_{13}+a_{12}b_{23}+a_{13}b_{33}\right) & \left(a_{21}b_{13}+a_{22}b_{23}+a_{23}b_{33}\right) & \left(a_{31}b_{13}+a_{32}b_{23}+a_{33}b_{33}\right)
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

which can be expanded out to be 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
R_{3}^{1} & =\begin{bmatrix}b_{11} & b_{21} & b_{31}\\
b_{12} & b_{22} & b_{32}\\
b_{13} & b_{23} & b_{33}
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}a_{11} & a_{21} & a_{31}\\
a_{12} & a_{22} & a_{32}\\
a_{13} & a_{23} & a_{33}
\end{bmatrix}\\
 & =\begin{bmatrix}\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right) & \left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right) & \left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{1}\right)\\
\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right) & \left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right) & \left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{2}\right)\\
\left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right) & \left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right) & \left(\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\mathbf{e}_{3}\right)
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right) & \left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right) & \left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\right)\\
\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right) & \left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right) & \left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\right)\\
\left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right) & \left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right) & \left(\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\cdot\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right)
\end{bmatrix}\\
 & =R_{2}^{1}R_{3}^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Pay special attention on how the forward transformations are multiplied.
 Unlike in subsection 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sub:Concatenation-of-Transformations"

\end_inset

 where the order of multiplication didn't matter since elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

 commute with the multiplication operator, the order matters in 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

.
 To make sense out of the order of concatenation, recall that a forward
 transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{3}^{1}$
\end_inset

 will transform the components a vector expressed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{3}$
\end_inset

 to be expressed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

, and the operation is written as 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{2}^{1}R_{3}^{2}\mathbf{v}^{3}$
\end_inset

.
 The components of the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{3}$
\end_inset

 will first be transformed to be expressed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 which leaves the operation 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{2}^{1}\mathbf{v}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Finally the components of the vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}^{2}$
\end_inset

 will be transformed to be expressed in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The derivation of the concatenation for backward transformations is simple
 now that we know how to concatenate forward transformations
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
R_{1}^{3} & =\left(R_{3}^{1}\right)^{-1}\\
 & =\left(R_{2}^{1}R_{3}^{2}\right)^{-1}\\
 & =\left(R_{3}^{2}\right)^{-1}\left(R_{2}^{1}\right)^{-1}\\
 & =R_{2}^{3}R_{1}^{2}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Note that the order of multiplication for backward transformations is opposite
 to concatenating forward transformations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us return to the example posed in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "fig:so3_concatenate"

\end_inset

.
 Using the embeddings of 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(2\right)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $SO\left(3\right)$
\end_inset

 we can easily express the forward transformations 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{2}^{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{3}^{2}$
\end_inset

 using the generalized coordinates 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{2}^{1}=\begin{bmatrix}1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \cos\left(\theta_{1}\right) & -\sin\left(\theta_{1}\right)\\
0 & \sin\left(\theta_{1}\right) & \cos\left(\theta_{1}\right)
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
R_{3}^{2}=\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(\theta_{2}\right) & 0 & \sin\left(\theta_{2}\right)\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
-\sin\left(\theta_{2}\right) & 0 & \cos\left(\theta_{2}\right)
\end{bmatrix}
\]

\end_inset

We can obtain the forward transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{3}^{1}$
\end_inset

 by concatenating 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{2}^{1}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{3}^{2}$
\end_inset

; 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
R_{3}^{1} & =R_{2}^{1}R_{3}^{2}\\
 & =\begin{bmatrix}1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \cos\left(\theta_{1}\right) & -\sin\left(\theta_{1}\right)\\
0 & \sin\left(\theta_{1}\right) & \cos\left(\theta_{1}\right)
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(\theta_{2}\right) & 0 & \sin\left(\theta_{2}\right)\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
-\sin\left(\theta_{2}\right) & 0 & \cos\left(\theta_{2}\right)
\end{bmatrix}\\
 & =\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(\theta_{2}\right) & 0 & \sin\left(\theta_{2}\right)\\
\sin\left(\theta_{1}\right)\sin\left(\theta_{2}\right) & \cos\left(\theta_{1}\right) & -\sin\left(\theta_{1}\right)\cos\left(\theta_{2}\right)\\
-\cos\left(\theta_{1}\right)\sin\left(\theta_{2}\right) & \sin\left(\theta_{1}\right) & \cos\left(\theta_{1}\right)\cos\left(\theta_{2}\right)
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{3}^{1}$
\end_inset

 is a rotation about 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{e}_{1}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}$
\end_inset

 followed by a rotation about 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2}$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We can verify that this transformation makes sense by looking at 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2}$
\end_inset

 in terms of the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Since the second transformation is about the basis vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{\tilde{e}}_{2}\cdot\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2}=1$
\end_inset

.
 This means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2}$
\end_inset

 is not affect by the second transformation, and that the transformation
 should only be parameterized by 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 This is the case since 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2}=0\mathbf{e}_{1}+\cos\left(\theta_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{2}+\sin\left(\theta_{1}\right)\mathbf{e}_{3}.
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Derivatives of SO
\begin_inset Formula $\left(3\right)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}=\left(O_{1},\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2},\mathbf{e}_{3}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}=\left(O_{2},\left\{ \tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1},\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2},\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{3}=\left(O_{3},\left\{ \bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1},\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2},\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 be standard frames in 
\begin_inset Formula $E^{3}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{1}$
\end_inset

 being the angular velocity of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 about the basis vector 
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{3}$
\end_inset

 representing the orientation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 after a time period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 as depicted in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "fig:SO3_derivative"

\end_inset

.
 Also, let 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{2}^{1}$
\end_inset

 denote the forward transformation that expresses the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

, and let 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{3}^{2}$
\end_inset

 denote the forward transformation that expresses the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{3}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 We can calculate the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{2}^{1}$
\end_inset

 by using the directional derivative and concatenations of forward transformatio
ns.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/SO3_Derivative.pdf
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:SO3_derivative"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{3}^{1}$
\end_inset

 is calculated as follows 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{d}{dt}F_{3}^{1} & =\frac{d}{dt}\left.\left(F_{2}^{1}F_{3}^{2}\right)\right|_{t=0}\\
 & =F_{2}^{1}\left.\left(\frac{d}{dt}F_{3}^{2}\right)\right|_{t=0}\\
 & =F_{2}^{1}\left.\left(\frac{d}{dt}\begin{bmatrix}1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \cos\left(t\omega_{1}\right) & -\sin\left(t\omega_{1}\right)\\
0 & \sin\left(t\omega_{1}\right) & \cos\left(t\omega_{1}\right)
\end{bmatrix}\right)\right|_{t=0}\\
 & =F_{2}^{1}\left.\begin{bmatrix}0 & 0 & 0\\
0 & -\omega_{1}\sin\left(t\omega_{1}\right) & -\omega_{1}\cos\left(t\omega_{1}\right)\\
0 & \omega_{1}\cos\left(t\omega_{1}\right) & -\omega_{1}\sin\left(t\omega_{1}\right)
\end{bmatrix}\right|_{t=0}\\
 & =F_{2}^{1}\begin{bmatrix}0 & 0 & 0\\
0 & 0 & -\omega_{1}\\
0 & \omega_{1} & 0
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now lets assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 is rotating about each of it's basis vectors at angular rates 
\begin_inset Formula $\omega_{i},\,i\in\left\{ 1,2,3\right\} $
\end_inset

, and that 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{3}$
\end_inset

 is the orientation of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 after a time period 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
 We can use the same process as above to calculate the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{2}^{1}$
\end_inset

 in the direction of 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{3}^{2}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{3}^{2}$
\end_inset

 can be properly represented as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
F_{3}^{2} & =\begin{bmatrix}1 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \cos\left(t\omega_{1}\right) & -\sin\left(t\omega_{1}\right)\\
0 & \sin\left(t\omega_{1}\right) & \cos\left(t\omega_{1}\right)
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(t\omega_{2}\right) & 0 & \sin\left(t\omega_{2}\right)\\
0 & 1 & 0\\
-\sin\left(t\omega_{2}\right) & 0 & \cos\left(t\omega_{2}\right)
\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}\cos\left(t\omega_{3}\right) & -\sin\left(t\omega_{3}\right) & 0\\
\sin\left(t\omega_{3}\right) & \cos\left(t\omega_{3}\right) & 0\\
0 & 0 & 1
\end{bmatrix}\\
 & =\begin{bmatrix}c_{\omega_{2}}c_{\omega_{3}} & -c_{\omega_{2}}s_{\omega_{3}} & s_{\omega_{2}}\\
s_{\omega_{1}}s_{\omega_{2}}c_{\omega_{3}}+c_{\omega_{1}}s_{\omega_{3}} & -s_{\omega_{1}}s_{\omega_{2}}s_{\omega_{3}}+c_{\omega_{1}}c_{\omega_{3}} & -s_{\omega_{1}}c_{\omega_{2}}\\
-c_{\omega_{1}}s_{\omega_{2}}c_{\omega_{1}}+s_{\omega_{1}}s_{\omega_{3}} & c_{\omega_{1}}s_{\omega_{2}}s_{\omega_{3}}+s_{\omega_{1}}c_{\omega_{3}} & c_{\omega_{1}}c_{\omega_{2}}
\end{bmatrix}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{\omega_{i}}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{\omega_{i}}$
\end_inset

 denote 
\begin_inset Formula $\sin\left(t\omega_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos\left(t\omega_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in\left\{ 1,2,3\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Note that the order of concatenation used to compose 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{3}^{2}$
\end_inset

 doesn't matter since we will be taking the limit as 
\begin_inset Formula $t\to0$
\end_inset

; thus we are interested in the infinitesimal rotations about each basis
 vector.
 Now taking the derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{3}^{1}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{d}{dt}F_{2}^{1} & =\frac{d}{dt}\left.\left(F_{2}^{1}F_{3}^{2}\right)\right|_{t=0}\\
 & =F_{2}^{1}\left.\left(\frac{d}{dt}F_{3}^{2}\right)\right|_{t=0}\\
 & =F_{2}^{1}\begin{bmatrix}0 & -\omega_{3} & \omega_{2}\\
\omega_{3} & 0 & -\omega_{1}\\
-\omega_{2} & \omega_{1} & 0
\end{bmatrix}\\
 & =F_{2}^{1}\left[\omega\right]_{\times}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\omega\right]_{\times}$
\end_inset

 denotes the skew symmetric matrix of the instantaneous angular velocities.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This derivative can be verified by taking the derivative of the identity
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{d}{dt}F^{\top}F & =I\\
\left(\frac{d}{dt}F^{\top}\right)F & =-F^{\top}\left(\frac{d}{dt}F\right)\\
\left[\omega\right]_{\times}^{\top}F^{\top}F & =-F^{\top}F\left[\omega\right]_{\times}\\
\left[\omega\right]_{\times}^{\top} & =-\left[\omega\right]_{\times}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The derivative of the forward transformation can also be derived using the
 exponential matrix.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
F\left(t\right)=F_{0}\exp\left(t\left[\omega\right]_{\times}\right)
\]

\end_inset

be a forward transformation where 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{0}$
\end_inset

 denotes the transformation at 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0$
\end_inset

, and
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\omega\right]_{\times}$
\end_inset

 denotes skew symmetric matrix representing the angular velocities about
 each bases of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 The derivative of the forward transformation w.r.t.
 time is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{d}{dt}F\left(t\right) & =\frac{d}{dt}\left.F_{0}\exp\left(t\left[\omega\right]_{\times}\right)\right|_{t=0}\\
 & =F_{0}\left.\left(\frac{d}{dt}\exp\left(t\left[\omega\right]_{\times}\right)\right)\right|_{t=0}\\
 & =F_{0}\left.\left(\frac{d}{dt}\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}\left(t\left[\omega\right]_{\times}\right)^{k}\right)\right|_{t=0}\\
 & =F_{0}\left.\left(\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}t^{k-1}\left(\left[\omega\right]_{\times}\right)^{k}\right)\right|_{t=0}\\
 & =F_{0}\left[\omega\right]_{\times}
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It can be easily verified that the derivative of the backward transformation
 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\frac{d}{dt}B & =\left[\omega\right]_{\times}^{\top}B\\
 & =-\left[\omega\right]_{\times}B
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Common Notation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A part of what makes rotation matrices so confusing to me, is that when
 I see them in literature all I see is the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 that denotes a rotation.
 If all I see is this 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

, I have no idea how it is defined.
 However, I have noticed a general trend with rotation matrix notation with
 mechanical systems which I will share here.
 In this section I will not define rotation matrices using the terminology
 of forward and backward transformation since you will probably never see
 them defined this way.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Simple Example
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When modeling a mechanical system you always need to have an inertial reference
 frame which I will denote as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{i}=\left(O_{i},\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2},\mathbf{e}_{3}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

.
 You always have an inertial reference frame since it never moves, and it's
 the frame in which Newtonian mechanics is valid, i.e., there are no pseudo
 forces.
 All other frames that are part of the mechanical system are generally placed
 at the center of mass of a rigid body.
 If a rigid body is not connected to any other rigid body, or if it's position
 or orientation is not determined by any other body, then the rotation matrix
 typically expresses the rigid body's basis in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{i}$
\end_inset

.
 If a rigid body 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 is connected to another rigid body 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 that affects it's orientation or position, then the corresponding rotation
 matrix expresses the basis of the frame associated with body 
\begin_inset Formula $b$
\end_inset

 in the frame associated with body 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
placement H
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\align center
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename figures/mechanicalSystemFrameExample.pdf
	width 40col%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:twoLinkArm"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example consider the simple two-link robot arm depicted in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "fig:twoLinkArm"

\end_inset

.
 The figure shows three frames.
 One frame is the inertial frame 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{i}=\left(O_{i},\left\{ \mathbf{e}_{1},\mathbf{e}_{2},\mathbf{e}_{3}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 and is positioned at the base of the first link.
 The other frames are placed at the center of mass of each link and are
 denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}=\left(O_{1},\left\{ \tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{1},\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{2},\tilde{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}=\left(O_{2},\left\{ \bar{\mathbf{e}}_{1},\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{2},\bar{\mathbf{e}}_{3}\right\} \right)$
\end_inset

.
 The first basis vector of each frame is pointing out of the figure so that
 each frame is right handed, and the third basis vector of each body frame
 points along the longer portion of the body.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Since there are three frames, there are three rotations that can be constructed.
 Note that the first rigid body's position and orientation is not affected
 by any other rigid bodies.
 Using common notation, we will define the first rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{1}^{i}$
\end_inset

 as the rotation that expresses the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{i}$
\end_inset

.
 The second rigid body's position and orientation is affected by the first
 rigid body.
 Because of this, we will define the second rotation 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{2}^{1}$
\end_inset

 as the rotation that expresses the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{1}$
\end_inset

.
 The final rotation is defined as 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{2}^{i}=R_{1}^{i}R_{2}^{1}$
\end_inset

 which expresses the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{2}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{i}$
\end_inset

.
 In a way, you typically define a set of rotations so that any frame can
 be expressed in the inertial frame.
 This is not always the case, so be careful.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Body-Centric vs Inertial Representation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The body centric representation expresses the basis of a body frame 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{b}$
\end_inset

 w.r.t.
 the basis of an inertial frame 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{i}$
\end_inset

, and the inertial representation expresses the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{i}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{b}$
\end_inset

; thus they are inverses of each other.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Summary
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are finally at the end of our little journey.
 Before you leave, let's review the main points.
 Vectors are objects that are invariant to change of basis, and can be expresses
 w.r.t.
 any basis using components, and the components of a vector transform contravari
antly to the basis when undergoing a change of basis.
 An active transformation denotes a rotation of a vector w.r.t.
 the same basis, and a passive transformation changes the components of
 a vector to express the vector w.r.t.
 another basis.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A transformation between bases is a transformation that expresses one basis
 w.r.t.
 another basis.
 The body centric representation expresses the basis of a body frame 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{b}$
\end_inset

 w.r.t.
 the basis of an inertial frame 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{i}$
\end_inset

, and the inertial representation expresses the basis of 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{i}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{F}^{b}$
\end_inset

; thus they are inverses of each other.
 Lastly, every transformation was derived from geometric principles, and
 we only used coordinates when needed to take derivatives.
\end_layout

